{"title_page": "Nicola Legrottaglie", "text_new": "{{redirect|Legrottaglie|the town|Grottaglie}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Nicola Legrottaglie\n| image = Nicola Legrottaglie.JPG\n| caption = Legrottaglie in 2010\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1976|10|20|df=y}}<ref name=Bio>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/nicola-legrottaglie_prs25524/person.shtml|title=Nicola Legrottaglie|publisher=[[Eurosport]]|accessdate=20 April 2010}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Gioia del Colle]], Italy<ref name=Bio/>\n| height = 1.85 m<ref name=Bio/>\n| position = [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|Centre back]]\n| currentclub = [[Delfino Pescara 1936|Pescara]] (manager)\n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[A.S. Bari|Bari]]\n| years1 = 1994\u20131998 | clubs1 = [[A.S. Bari|Bari]] | caps1 = 17 | goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 1996\u20131997 | clubs2 = \u2192 [[A.C. Pistoiese|Pistoiese]] (loan) | caps2 = 31 | goals2 = 3\n| years3 = 1997\u20131998 | clubs3 = \u2192 [[A.C. Prato|Prato]] (loan) | caps3 = 26 | goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 1998\u20132003 | clubs4 = [[A.C. ChievoVerona|Chievo]] | caps4 = 66 | goals4 = 6\n| years5 = 2000 | clubs5 = \u2192 [[A.C. Reggiana 1919|Reggiana]] (loan) | caps5 = 4 | goals5 = 1\n| years6 = 2000\u20132001 | clubs6 = \u2192 [[Modena F.C.|Modena]] (co-ownership) | caps6 = 32 | goals6 = 1\n| years7 = 2003\u20132011 | clubs7 = [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] | caps7 = 114 | goals7 = 8\n| years8 = 2005 | clubs8 = \u2192 [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]] (loan) | caps8 = 9 | goals8 = 0\n| years9 = 2005\u20132006 | clubs9 = \u2192 [[A.C. Siena|Siena]] (loan) | caps9 = 28 | goals9 = 0\n| years10 = 2011 | clubs10 = [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] | caps10 = 1 | goals10 = 0\n| years11 = 2011\u20132014 | clubs11 = [[Calcio Catania|Catania]] | caps11 = 76 | goals11 = 8\n| totalcaps = 404 | totalgoals = 27\n| nationalyears1 = 2002\u20132009 | nationalteam1 = [[Italy national football team|Italy]] | nationalcaps1 = 16 | nationalgoals1 = 1\n| manageryears1 = 2014\u20132015 | managerclubs1 = [[A.S. Bari|Bari]] (youth)\n| manageryears2 = 2015\u20132016 | managerclubs2 = [[S.S. Akragas Citt\u00e0 dei Templi|Akragas]]\n| manageryears3 = 2017 | managerclubs3 = [[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]] (assistant)\n| manageryears4 = 2019\u20132020 | managerclubs4 = [[Delfino Pescara 1936|Pescara]] (youth)\n| manageryears5 = 2020\u2013 | managerclubs5 = [[Delfino Pescara 1936|Pescara]]\n}}\n\n'''Nicola Legrottaglie''' ({{IPA-it|ni\u02c8k\u0254\u02d0la le\u0261rot\u02c8ta\u028e\u028ee}}; born 20 October 1976) is an Italian retired [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|central defender]], and the [[Manager (association football)|manager]] of [[Delfino Pescara 1936]].\n\nIn a senior career that lasted two full decades, he amassed [[Serie A]] totals of 259 matches and 22 goals over 12 seasons, representing in the competition [[A.C. ChievoVerona|Chievo]], [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]], [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]], [[A.C. Siena|Siena]], [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] and [[Calcio Catania|Catania]]. He [[2010\u201311 Serie A|won the 2011 national championship with the fifth club]].\n\nLegrottaglie earned 16 [[Cap (sport)|caps]] for [[Italy national football team|Italy]], appearing for the nation at the [[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup|2009 Confederations Cup]].\n\n==Playing career==\n===Club===\n====Early years / Chievo====\nBorn in [[Gioia del Colle]], [[Province of Bari]], Legrottaglie began his career with [[A.S. Bari]], having loan spells at [[A.C. Pistoiese]] and [[A.C. Prato]]. Following his return in June 1998 he was sold to [[A.C. ChievoVerona]] of the [[Serie B]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/1998/giugno/05/Bologna_passi_avanti_per_Esposito_ga_0_9806059313.shtml|title=Bologna: passi avanti per Esposito e Morfeo|trans-title=Bologna: moves for Esposito and Morfeo|newspaper=[[La Gazzetta dello Sport]]|first=Carlo|last=Laudisa|language=Italian|date=5 June 1998|accessdate=9 April 2010}}</ref> appearing rarely in [[1999\u20132000 Serie B|his second season]] with the team and, in January 2000, moved on loan to [[A.C. Reggiana 1919]] in the [[Lega Pro Prima Divisione|third division]]; with his new club he also found playing opportunities hard to come by and, after his return to [[Verona]], moved to the same level and also on loan, now with [[Modena F.C.|Modena FC]].\n\nLegrottaglie was ever-present in the starting XI during his spell at Modena, subsequently returning to Chievo for their [[2001\u201302 Serie A|first-ever season]] in [[Serie A]]. He only appeared in 15 games as the team [[2002\u201303 UEFA Cup|qualified]] for the [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]]; in [[2002\u201303 Serie A|his second season]], the defender established himself as a top division player, scoring four goals in 32 league appearances to help to another comfortable mid-table finish (seventh).\n\n====Juventus====\nIn the 2003 off-season, Legrottaglie was rewarded with a move to [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus FC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsId=75698.html|title=Legrottaglie relishing Juve move|publisher=UEFA|date=19 June 2003|accessdate=1 November 2010}}</ref> The club paid [[Euro|\u20ac]]7.55million for his services to Chievo, \u20ac0.45 million being used in selling 50% of the rights to [[Giuseppe Sculli]], [[Matteo Paro]] and [[Daniele Gastaldello]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.juventus.com/site/filesite/finance/comunicatipricesensitive/19_giu_2003_chi.pdf|title=Juventus Football Club: Accordo con la societ\u00e0 A.C. Chievo Verona per l\u2019acquisizione del calciatore Nicola Legrottaglie|trans-title=Juventus Football Club: Deal with A.C. Chievo Verona for acquisition of footballer Nicola Legrottaglie|publisher=Juventus F.C|language=Italian|date=19 June 2003|accessdate=13 July 2009}}</ref>\n\nLegrottaglie was a full member of the first-team squad in the [[2003\u201304 Serie A|2003\u201304 season]], taking part in 21 games and netting twice under coach [[Marcello Lippi]]. However, following the appointment of new manager [[Fabio Capello]] he fell down the defensive pecking order, making just two appearances in five months; he thus moved on loan to [[Bologna F.C. 1909]] in the 2005 January [[transfer window]], playing 11 matches \u2013 including twice in the promotion playoffs \u2013 for the [[Emilia-Romagna]] side.<ref name=TUTTO>{{cite web|url=https://m.tuttojuve.com/gli-eroi-bianconeri/gli-eroi-in-bianconero-nicola-legrottaglie-393029|title=Gli eroi in bianconero: Nicola LEGROTTAGLIE|trans-title=The heroes in black and white: Nicola LEGROTTAGLIE|publisher=Tutto Juve|language=Italian|date=27 October 2017|accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Nicola Legrottaglie (2008).jpg|thumb|left|Legrotagglie playing for [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] in 2008]]\nLegrottaglie returned to Juventus in the summer of 2005, but was instantly loaned out to [[A.C. Siena]] for the [[2005\u201306 Serie A|2005\u201306 campaign]],<ref name=TUTTO/> alongside teammate [[Igor Tudor]] and some youth players. While at the latter he was again a regular, as his team finally avoided relegation.\n\nBack at ''Juve'', and as an experienced player, Legrottaglie was expected to play a role in the club's attempt to return to the top level following the ''[[2006 Italian football scandal|2006 Calciopoli]]'' scandal. However, he would only take the field in ten fixtures out of 42 \u2013 also being shown a [[Ejection (sports)|red card]] \u2013 in a [[2006\u201307 Serie B|promotion as champions]].\n\nSubsequently, Legrottaglie came very close to complete a transfer to [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.]] on a three-year contract, worth [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]1.1 million per season. The Turkish were set to pay \u00a31.6 million to acquire his services, but negotiations broke down at the last minute and hence, the player remained in [[Torino]]; under [[Claudio Ranieri]] he started the [[2007\u201308 Serie A|new season]] right where he left off, on the [[Substitute (association football)|substitutes' bench]], being fourth-choice behind [[Jorge Andrade]], [[Jean-Alain Boumsong]] and [[Domenico Criscito]].<ref name=GAZZETTA>{{cite news|url=https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Squadre/Juventus/Primo_Piano/2007/09_Settembre/28/legrottaglie.shtml|title=Legrottaglie, la rivincita \u2013 \"Dimostrer\u00f2 chi sono\"|trans-title=Legrottaglie, the claim \u2013 \"I will show my worth\"|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|first=Alberto|last=Mauro|language=Italian|date=28 September 2007|accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nJust four matches into the season, however, a serious [[knee]] injury sidelined Andrade for several months,<ref name=GAZZETTA/> and Legrottaglie was promoted to the starting eleven for the game against [[Reggina Calcio]] on 26 September, scoring the opener in a 4\u20130 rout.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=224381&cc=5739|title=Juventus 4\u20130 Reggina|publisher=[[ESPN FC|ESPN Soccernet]]|date=26 September 2007|accessdate=1 December 2011}}</ref> Criscito was loaned out to [[Genoa C.F.C.]] in January 2008 and, from then onwards, he paired with [[Giorgio Chiellini]] in central defence as the side allowed just nine goals in the first 14 matches following Andrade's injury (37 overall), finishing in third place; his contract ran originally until 30 June 2008, but in October 2007, due to his excellent form, he was awarded a two-year extension.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tuttomercatoweb.com/?action=read&id=78830|title=UFFICIALE: Legrottaglie rinnova con la Juventus|trans-title=OFFICIAL: Legrottaglie renews with Juventus|publisher=Tutto Mercato Web|first=Alessio|last=Calfapietra|language=Italian|date=29 October 2007|accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn [[2008\u201309 Serie A|2008\u201309]], Legrottaglie continued to be first-choice despite the arrival of [[Olof Mellberg]] from [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] (Andrade also was expected to return to first-team action, but he suffered a second serious knee injury).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Squadre/Juventus/Primo_Piano/2009/01/08/legrottaglie.shtml|title=Legrottaglie: \"Un altro gol? Al Siena sarebbe magico\"|trans-title=Legrottaglie: \"Another goal? It would be magical against Siena\"|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|first=Alberto|last=Mauro|language=Italian|date=8 January 2009|accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref> In September 2008, one month shy of his 32nd birthday, he signed another deal until June 2011, and played 27 league matches in a runner-up finish, thus [[2009\u201310 UEFA Champions League|qualifying]] for the [[UEFA Champions League]] for the second consecutive year; veteran [[Fabio Cannavaro]] returned to the club following his spell with [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]], and this relegated him to the bench for parts of the [[2009\u201310 Serie A|2009\u201310 campaign]] \u2013 he ended with 19 league appearances, netting once.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sport.sky.it/calcio/fotogallery/2010/02/06/livorno_juventus.html|title=Il fotoracconto di Livorno-Juventus|trans-title=The Livorno-Juventus photo gallery|publisher=[[Sky Sport (Italy)|Sky Sport]]|language=Italian|date=6 February 2010|accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nLegrottaglie was injured during training in late May 2010, and thus missed out on the [[United States]] tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.juventus.com/site/eng/NEWS_newsseriea_33B5B4B1579B41E9B42DA0156E394B5E.asp|title=Juventus land in New York|publisher=Juventus F.C|date=20 May 2010|accessdate=21 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n====Milan====\nOn 31 January 2011, after Juventus signed central defender [[Andrea Barzagli]], the 34-year-old Legrottaglie \u2013 who made just eight appearances in all competitions comprised during the first half of [[2010\u201311 Serie A|the season]], under new manager [[Luigi Delneri]] \u2013 left on a [[Free transfer (association football)|free transfer]] for fellow league side [[A.C. Milan]], signing a six-month deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.juventus.com/site/eng/NEWS_newsseriea_E9ECFAC7927D49668543A6FB21DD457D.asp|title=Legrottaglie joins Milan|publisher=Juventus F.C|date=31 January 2011|accessdate=31 January 2011}}</ref> However, he was only able to make one league appearance for the eventual champions due to a serious head injury suffered during a 0\u20130 draw with [[S.S. Lazio]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=304651&cc=5739|title=Leaders held to stalemate|publisher=ESPN Soccernet|date=1 February 2011|accessdate=1 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/notizie-ultima-ora/Atri_sport/Milan-Bonera-Legrottaglie-ospedale/01-02-2011/2-A_000142260.shtml|title=Milan: Bonera e Legrottaglie in ospedale|trans-title=Milan: Bonera and Legrottaglie in hospital|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=1 February 2011|accessdate=9 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nLegrottaglie was released on 30 June, following the expiration of his contract.\n\n====Catania====\nOn 24 August 2011, Legrottaglie joined [[Calcio Catania]] on a two-year contract. He scored on his official debut, a 3\u20133 away draw against [[Novara Calcio]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/327149?cc=5739|title=Novara 3\u20133 Catania|publisher=ESPN Soccernet|date=2 October 2011|accessdate=4 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nLegrottaglie revived his career overall under [[Vincenzo Montella]]. He finished [[2011\u201312 Serie A|2011\u201312]] with 35 official games and six goals, helping the [[Sicily|Sicilians]] to a fourth successive season in which they broke their record points total in Serie A, finishing 11th.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportmediaset.mediaset.it/calcio/calcioserieA/articoli/78932/legrottaglie-gol-catania-europeo-.shtml|title=Legrottaglie-gol, Catania \"europeo\"|trans-title=Legrottaglie-goal, \"European\" Catania|publisher=Sport Media Set|language=Italian|date=18 March 2012|accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Squadre/Catania/29-03-2012/catania-profumo-d-europa-montella-fabbrica-gol-91768411327.shtml?refresh_ce-cp|title=Catania, profumo d'Europa \u2013 Montella guida il Piccolo Barcellona|trans-title=Catania, scent of Europe \u2013 Montella at the helm of Little Barcelona|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|first=Giovanni|last=Finocchiaro|language=Italian|date=29 March 2012|accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.calcionews24.com/catania-legrottaglie-montella-un-predestinato-229570/|title=Catania, Legrottaglie: \"Montella un predestinato\"|trans-title=Catania, Legrottaglie: \u201cMontella is a natural\u201d|publisher=Calcio News 24|language=Italian|date=28 April 2012|accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/it/news/2/serie-a/2012/05/07/3086561/legrottaglie-catania-amore-che-durer%C3%A0-a-lungo-mi-sono|title=Legrottaglie-Catania, amore che durer\u00e0 a lungo: \"Mi sono trovato benissimo, da qui non mi muovo\"|trans-title=Legrottaglie-Catania, love to last forever: \"I felt terrific, I'm staying put\"|publisher=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|first=Daniele|last=Gamberini|language=Italian|date=7 May 2012|accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===International===\nLegrottaglie made his debut for [[Italy national football team|Italy]] on 20 November 2002, in a [[Exhibition game|friendly match]] with [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]] in [[Pescara]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.italia1910.com/partita.asp?idpartita=608|title=Italia-Turchia (1\u20131)|trans-title=Italy-Turkey (1\u20131)|publisher=Italia 1910|language=Italian|accessdate=12 February 2015}}</ref> and went on to appear in a further six matches in a one-year span, mostly friendlies. He scored his only goal in April 2003, in a 2\u20131 victory over [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]].<ref name=GOAL>{{cite web|url=http://www.italia1910.com/partita.asp?d=30/04/2003|title=Italia-Svizzera (2\u20131)|trans-title=Italy-Switzerland (2\u20131)|publisher=Italia 1910|language=Italian|accessdate=12 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nFollowing solid performances at Juventus, Legrottaglie received his first [[Cap (sport)|cap]] in four years, appearing in a friendly against [[Austria national football team|Austria]] while filling in for injured teammate Chiellini in an 18 August 2008 contest held in [[Nice]]. His former Juventus coach Lippi was in charge of the national team.\n\nOn 2 May 2010, 33-year-old Legrottaglie was included in a 29-man provisional list for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]], attending the training camp in [[Rome]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.figc.it/it/204/24432/2010/05/News.shtml|title=Verso il Mondiale. Ventinove Azzurri convocati per lo stage di Roma|trans-title=Towards the World Cup. Twenty-nine Blues called to training camp in Rome|publisher=[[Italian Football Federation]]|language=Italian|date=2 May 2010|accessdate=11 May 2010|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100505035854/http://www.figc.it/it/204/24432/2010/05/News.shtml|archive-date=5 May 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> but was subsequently dropped from the 30-player list submitted to [[FIFA]] on the 11th, with [[Villarreal CF]]'s [[Giuseppe Rossi]] and [[A.S. Roma]]'s [[Daniele De Rossi]] taking his place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.figc.it/it/204/24545/2010/05/News.shtml|title=Ufficializzata la lista dei 30: C\u2019\u00e8 Giuseppe Rossi al posto di Legrottaglie|trans-title=List of 30 players official: Giuseppe Rossi for Legrottaglie|publisher=Italian Football Federation|language=Italian|date=11 May 2010|accessdate=11 May 2010|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100514144154/http://www.figc.it/it/204/24545/2010/05/News.shtml|archive-date=14 May 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> His only major international tournament was the [[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup]] in [[South Africa]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Nazionale/04-06-2009/santon-sud-africa-50488544529.shtml|title=Santon in Sud Africa \u2013 Pazzini resta fuori|trans-title=Santon in South Africa \u2013 Pazzini remains excluded|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=4 June 2009|accessdate=17 January 2017}}</ref> with Italy exiting in the group stage.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/international/5596826/Confederations-Cup-Brazil-and-Kaka-humiliate-Italy.html|title=Confederations Cup: Brazil and Kaka humiliate Italy|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|first=Duncan|last=White|date=21 June 2009|accessdate=17 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n====International goals====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! # !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1. || 30 April 2003 || [[Geneva]], Switzerland || {{fb|SUI}} || 2\u20131 || Win || [[Exhibition game|Friendly]]<ref name=GOAL/>\n|}\n\n==Coaching career==\nLegrottaglie retired at the end of the [[2013\u201314 Serie A|2013\u201314 campaign]] as Catania suffered top-flight relegation, aged nearly 38. He then returned to Bari after 18 years, being appointed under-17 team manager.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://corrieredelmezzogiorno.corriere.it/bari/notizie/sport/2014/18-luglio-2014/largo-giovani-bari-punta-vivaiolegrottaglie-allenera-allievi-223591450035.shtml|title=Largo ai giovani, il Bari punta sul vivaio Legrottaglie allener\u00e0 gli allievi|trans-title=Make way for the young, Bari focus on academy Legrottaglie will coach the students|newspaper=[[Corriere del Mezzogiorno]]|first=Davide|last=Lattanzi|language=Italian|date=18 July 2014|accessdate=27 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nLegrottaglie took his first role as a head coach in July 2015, accepting an offer from Sicilian [[Lega Pro]] club [[S.S. Akragas Citt\u00e0 dei Templi]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calciomercato/17-07-2015/legrottaglie-riparte-sicilia-sara-allenatore-akragas-120593968701.shtml|title=Legrottaglie riparte dalla Sicilia: sar\u00e0 l'allenatore dell'Akragas|trans-title=Legrottaglie leaves for Sicily: he will be Akragas' coach|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=9 January 2017|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref> He resigned the following January due to poor results<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tuttosport.com/news/calcio/calciomercato/2016/01/17-7628064/calciomercato_akragas_legrottaglie_lascia_la_panchina/|title=Calciomercato Akragas, Legrottaglie lascia la panchina|trans-title=Calciomercato Akragas, Legrottaglie leaves the bench|newspaper=[[Tuttosport]]|language=Italian|date=9 January 2017|accessdate=17 January 2016}}</ref> and, on 9 January 2017, was named new assistant to [[Massimo Rastelli]] at [[Cagliari Calcio]] in the [[Italian football league system|Italian top division]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagliaricalcio.com/news/ultimissime/15706/legrottaglie-nello-staff-tecnico-rossoblu|title=Legrottaglie nello staff tecnico rossobl\u00f9|trans-title=Legrottaglie in red-and-blue staff|publisher=Cagliari Calcio|language=Italian|date=9 January 2017|accessdate=9 January 2017}}</ref> in October, as the latter was dismissed, he too left.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagliarinews24.com/legrottaglie-saluta-cagliari-grazie/|title=Legrottaglie saluta Cagliari: \u00abRischi del mestiere, grazie a tutti\u00bb|trans-title=Legrottaglie salutes Cagliari: \u00abGoes with the territory, thanks everybody\u00bb|publisher=Cagliari News 24|first=Sergio|last=Cadeddu|language=Italian|date=17 October 2017|accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 June 2019, Legrottaglie was announced as the new under-19 manager of [[Delfino Pescara 1936]], replacing [[Luciano Zauri]] after the latter's promotion as first-team manager.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ilpescara.it/sport/calcio/nicola-legrottaglie-allenatore-primavera-pescara.html|title=Nicola Legrottaglie nuovo allenatore della Primavera del Pescara|trans-title=Nicola Legrottaglie new Pescara ''Primavera'' manager|newspaper=Il Pescara|language=Italian|date=24 June 2019|accessdate=7 July 2019}}</ref> On 21 January 2020, he was promoted to head coach after Zauri's resignation from his post.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.corrieredellosport.it/news/calcio/serie-b/pescara/2020/01/21-65843497/pescara_panchina_a_legrottaglie_e_ufficiale/|title=Pescara, panchina a Legrottaglie: \u00e8 ufficiale|trans-title=Pescara, Legrottaglie to the bench: it's official|newspaper=[[Corriere dello Sport \u2013 Stadio|Corriere dello Sport]]|language=Italian|date=21 January 2020|accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nLegrottaglie was praised by pundits for his physical attributes and his ability in the air, making him a goal threat from set pieces.<ref name=Juventinologo>{{cite web|url=http://juventinologo.blogspot.ca/2009/04/nicola-legrottaglie-scheda-tecnica.html|title=Nicola Legrottaglie \u2013 Scheda tecnica|trans-title=Nicola Legrottaglie \u2013 Technical report|publisher=Juventinologo|language=Italian|date=16 April 2009|accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref> A strong yet elegant player, he excelled in sliding challenges and at organising high defensive lines, also being gifted with good technical ability, passing range and vision, which allowed him to advance into the midfield. He was also tactically versatile, excelling at reading the game and possessing a powerful shot from distance.\n\nDespite his reputation, Legrottaglie was also criticised at times for inconsistency and lapses in man-marking.<ref name=Juventinologo/>\n\n==Personal life==\nLegrottaglie attracted controversy when he came out strongly against [[homosexuality]], calling it a \"sin\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/10/italy/2009/03/18/1161761/nicola-legrottaglie-insists-homosexuality-is-a-sin|title=Nicola Legrottaglie insists 'homosexuality is a sin'|publisher=Goal|first=Salvatore|last=Landolina|date=18 March 2009|accessdate=18 March 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n'''Juventus'''<ref name=SW>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/coaches/nicola-legrottaglie/17687/|title=N. Legrottaglie \u2013 Trophies|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=21 December 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Supercoppa Italiana]]: [[2003 Supercoppa Italiana|2003]]\n*[[Serie B]]: [[2006\u201307 Serie B|2006\u201307]]\n*[[Coppa Italia]] runner-up: [[2004 Coppa Italia Final|2003\u201304]]\n\n'''Milan'''<ref name=SW/>\n*[[Serie A]]: [[2010\u201311 Serie A|2010\u201311]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081217140125/https://www.juventus.com/site/ita/TAS_schedagiocatoreprimasquadra_417D659ABA15488388474BCB517B9004.asp Juventus official profile] {{in lang|it}}\n*{{TuttoCalciatori|Legrottaglie_Nicola}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120829155902/http://www.figc.it/nazionali/DettaglioConvocato?codiceConvocato=1524&squadra=1 National team data] {{in lang|it}} {{dead link|date=March 2019}}\n*{{NFT player|3373}}\n\n{{Italy Squad 2009 FIFA Confederations Cup}}\n{{Delfino Pescara 1936 squad}}\n{{Serie B managers}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Legrottaglie, Nicola}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Taranto]]\n[[Category:Italian Protestants]]\n[[Category:Italian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Serie B players]]\n[[Category:Serie C players]]\n[[Category:S.S.C. Bari players]]\n[[Category:U.S. Pistoiese 1921 players]]\n[[Category:A.C. Prato players]]\n[[Category:A.C. ChievoVerona players]]\n[[Category:Reggio Audace F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Modena F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Juventus F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bologna F.C. 1909 players]]\n[[Category:Robur Siena players]]\n[[Category:A.C. Milan players]]\n[[Category:Calcio Catania players]]\n[[Category:Italy international footballers]]\n[[Category:2009 FIFA Confederations Cup players]]\n[[Category:Italian football managers]]\n[[Category:Serie B managers]]\n[[Category:Delfino Pescara 1936 managers]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Legrottaglie|the town|Grottaglie}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Nicola Legrottaglie\n| image = Nicola Legrottaglie.JPG\n| caption = Legrottaglie in 2010\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1976|10|20|df=y}}<ref name=Bio>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/nicola-legrottaglie_prs25524/person.shtml|title=Nicola Legrottaglie|publisher=[[Eurosport]]|accessdate=20 April 2010}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Gioia del Colle]], Italy<ref name=Bio/>\n| height = 1.85 m<ref name=Bio/>\n| position = [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|Centre back]]\n| currentclub = [[Delfino Pescara 1936|Pescara]] (manager)\n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[A.S. Bari|Bari]]\n| years1 = 1994\u20131998 | clubs1 = [[A.S. Bari|Bari]] | caps1 = 17 | goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 1996\u20131997 | clubs2 = \u2192 [[A.C. Pistoiese|Pistoiese]] (loan) | caps2 = 31 | goals2 = 3\n| years3 = 1997\u20131998 | clubs3 = \u2192 [[A.C. Prato|Prato]] (loan) | caps3 = 26 | goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 1998\u20132003 | clubs4 = [[A.C. ChievoVerona|Chievo]] | caps4 = 66 | goals4 = 6\n| years5 = 2000 | clubs5 = \u2192 [[A.C. Reggiana 1919|Reggiana]] (loan) | caps5 = 4 | goals5 = 1\n| years6 = 2000\u20132001 | clubs6 = \u2192 [[Modena F.C.|Modena]] (co-ownership) | caps6 = 32 | goals6 = 1\n| years7 = 2003\u20132011 | clubs7 = [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] | caps7 = 114 | goals7 = 8\n| years8 = 2005 | clubs8 = \u2192 [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]] (loan) | caps8 = 9 | goals8 = 0\n| years9 = 2005\u20132006 | clubs9 = \u2192 [[A.C. Siena|Siena]] (loan) | caps9 = 28 | goals9 = 0\n| years10 = 2011 | clubs10 = [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] | caps10 = 1 | goals10 = 0\n| years11 = 2011\u20132014 | clubs11 = [[Calcio Catania|Catania]] | caps11 = 76 | goals11 = 8\n| totalcaps = 404 | totalgoals = 27\n| nationalyears1 = 2002\u20132009 | nationalteam1 = [[Italy national football team|Italy]] | nationalcaps1 = 16 | nationalgoals1 = 1\n| manageryears1 = 2014\u20132015 | managerclubs1 = [[A.S. Bari|Bari]] (youth)\n| manageryears2 = 2015\u20132016 | managerclubs2 = [[S.S. Akragas Citt\u00e0 dei Templi|Akragas]]\n| manageryears3 = 2017 | managerclubs3 = [[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]] (assistant)\n| manageryears4 = 2019\u20132020 | managerclubs4 = [[Delfino Pescara 1936|Pescara]] (youth)\n| manageryears5 = 2020\u2013 | managerclubs5 = [[Delfino Pescara 1936|Pescara]]\n}}\n\n'''Nicola Legrottaglie''' ({{IPA-it|ni\u02c8k\u0254\u02d0la le\u0261rot\u02c8ta\u028e\u028ee}}; born 20 October 1976) is an Italian retired [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|central defender]], and the [[Manager (association football)|manager]] of [[Delfino Pescara 1936]].\n\nIn a senior career that lasted two full decades, he amassed [[Serie A]] totals of 259 matches and 22 goals over 12 seasons, representing in the competition [[A.C. ChievoVerona|Chievo]], [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]], [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]], [[A.C. Siena|Siena]], [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] and [[Calcio Catania|Catania]]. He [[2010\u201311 Serie A|won the 2011 national championship with the fifth club]].\n\nLegrottaglie earned 16 [[Cap (sport)|caps]] for [[Italy national football team|Italy]], appearing for the nation at the [[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup|2009 Confederations Cup]].\n\n==Playing career==\n===Club===\n====Early years / Chievo====\nBorn in [[Gioia del Colle]], [[Province of Bari]], Legrottaglie began his career with [[A.S. Bari]], having loan spells at [[A.C. Pistoiese]] and [[A.C. Prato]]. Following his return in June 1998 he was sold to [[A.C. ChievoVerona]] of the [[Serie B]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/1998/giugno/05/Bologna_passi_avanti_per_Esposito_ga_0_9806059313.shtml|title=Bologna: passi avanti per Esposito e Morfeo|trans-title=Bologna: moves for Esposito and Morfeo|newspaper=[[La Gazzetta dello Sport]]|first=Carlo|last=Laudisa|language=Italian|date=5 June 1998|accessdate=9 April 2010}}</ref> appearing rarely in [[1999\u20132000 Serie B|his second season]] with the team and, in January 2000, moved on loan to [[A.C. Reggiana 1919]] in the [[Lega Pro Prima Divisione|third division]]; with his new club he also found playing opportunities hard to come by and, after his return to [[Verona]], moved to the same level and also on loan, now with [[Modena F.C.|Modena FC]].\n\nLegrottaglie was ever-present in the starting XI during his spell at Modena, subsequently returning to Chievo for their [[2001\u201302 Serie A|first-ever season]] in [[Serie A]]. He only appeared in 15 games as the team [[2002\u201303 UEFA Cup|qualified]] for the [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]]; in [[2002\u201303 Serie A|his second season]], the defender established himself as a top division player, scoring four goals in 32 league appearances to help to another comfortable mid-table finish (seventh).\n\n====Juventus====\nIn the 2003 off-season, Legrottaglie was rewarded with a move to [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus FC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsId=75698.html|title=Legrottaglie relishing Juve move|publisher=UEFA|date=19 June 2003|accessdate=1 November 2010}}</ref> The club paid [[Euro|\u20ac]]7.55million for his services to Chievo, \u20ac0.45 million being used in selling 50% of the rights to [[Giuseppe Sculli]], [[Matteo Paro]] and [[Daniele Gastaldello]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.juventus.com/site/filesite/finance/comunicatipricesensitive/19_giu_2003_chi.pdf|title=Juventus Football Club: Accordo con la societ\u00e0 A.C. Chievo Verona per l\u2019acquisizione del calciatore Nicola Legrottaglie|trans-title=Juventus Football Club: Deal with A.C. Chievo Verona for acquisition of footballer Nicola Legrottaglie|publisher=Juventus F.C|language=Italian|date=19 June 2003|accessdate=13 July 2009}}</ref>\n\nLegrottaglie was a full member of the first-team squad in the [[2003\u201304 Serie A|2003\u201304 season]], taking part in 21 games and netting twice under coach [[Marcello Lippi]]. However, following the appointment of new manager [[Fabio Capello]] he fell down the defensive pecking order, making just two appearances in five months; he thus moved on loan to [[Bologna F.C. 1909]] in the 2005 January [[transfer window]], playing 11 matches \u2013 including twice in the promotion playoffs \u2013 for the [[Emilia-Romagna]] side.<ref name=TUTTO>{{cite web|url=https://m.tuttojuve.com/gli-eroi-bianconeri/gli-eroi-in-bianconero-nicola-legrottaglie-393029|title=Gli eroi in bianconero: Nicola LEGROTTAGLIE|trans-title=The heroes in black and white: Nicola LEGROTTAGLIE|publisher=Tutto Juve|language=Italian|date=27 October 2017|accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Nicola Legrottaglie (2008).jpg|thumb|left|Legrotagglie playing for [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] in 2008]]\nLegrottaglie returned to Juventus in the summer of 2005, but was instantly loaned out to [[A.C. Siena]] for the [[2005\u201306 Serie A|2005\u201306 campaign]],<ref name=TUTTO/> alongside teammate [[Igor Tudor]] and some youth players. While at the latter he was again a regular, as his team finally avoided relegation.\n\nBack at ''Juve'', and as an experienced player, Legrottaglie was expected to play a role in the club's attempt to return to the top level following the ''[[2006 Italian football scandal|2006 Calciopoli]]'' scandal. However, he would only take the field in ten fixtures out of 42 \u2013 also being shown a [[Ejection (sports)|red card]] \u2013 in a [[2006\u201307 Serie B|promotion as champions]].\n\nSubsequently, Legrottaglie came very close to complete a transfer to [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.]] on a three-year contract, worth [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]1.1 million per season. The Turkish were set to pay \u00a31.6 million to acquire his services, but negotiations broke down at the last minute and hence, the player remained in [[Torino]]; under [[Claudio Ranieri]] he started the [[2007\u201308 Serie A|new season]] right where he left off, on the [[Substitute (association football)|substitutes' bench]], being fourth-choice behind [[Jorge Andrade]], [[Jean-Alain Boumsong]] and [[Domenico Criscito]].<ref name=GAZZETTA>{{cite news|url=https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Squadre/Juventus/Primo_Piano/2007/09_Settembre/28/legrottaglie.shtml|title=Legrottaglie, la rivincita \u2013 \"Dimostrer\u00f2 chi sono\"|trans-title=Legrottaglie, the claim \u2013 \"I will show my worth\"|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|first=Alberto|last=Mauro|language=Italian|date=28 September 2007|accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nJust four matches into the season, however, a serious [[knee]] injury sidelined Andrade for several months,<ref name=GAZZETTA/> and Legrottaglie was promoted to the starting eleven for the game against [[Reggina Calcio]] on 26 September, scoring the opener in a 4\u20130 rout.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=224381&cc=5739|title=Juventus 4\u20130 Reggina|publisher=[[ESPN FC|ESPN Soccernet]]|date=26 September 2007|accessdate=1 December 2011}}</ref> Criscito was loaned out to [[Genoa C.F.C.]] in January 2008 and, from then onwards, he paired with [[Giorgio Chiellini]] in central defence as the side allowed just nine goals in the first 14 matches following Andrade's injury (37 overall), finishing in third place; his contract ran originally until 30 June 2008, but in October 2007, due to his excellent form, he was awarded a two-year extension.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tuttomercatoweb.com/?action=read&id=78830|title=UFFICIALE: Legrottaglie rinnova con la Juventus|trans-title=OFFICIAL: Legrottaglie renews with Juventus|publisher=Tutto Mercato Web|first=Alessio|last=Calfapietra|language=Italian|date=29 October 2007|accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn [[2008\u201309 Serie A|2008\u201309]], Legrottaglie continued to be first-choice despite the arrival of [[Olof Mellberg]] from [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] (Andrade also was expected to return to first-team action, but he suffered a second serious knee injury).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Squadre/Juventus/Primo_Piano/2009/01/08/legrottaglie.shtml|title=Legrottaglie: \"Un altro gol? Al Siena sarebbe magico\"|trans-title=Legrottaglie: \"Another goal? It would be magical against Siena\"|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|first=Alberto|last=Mauro|language=Italian|date=8 January 2009|accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref> In September 2008, one month shy of his 32nd birthday, he signed another deal until June 2011, and played 27 league matches in a runner-up finish, thus [[2009\u201310 UEFA Champions League|qualifying]] for the [[UEFA Champions League]] for the second consecutive year; veteran [[Fabio Cannavaro]] returned to the club following his spell with [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]], and this relegated him to the bench for parts of the [[2009\u201310 Serie A|2009\u201310 campaign]] \u2013 he ended with 19 league appearances, netting once.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sport.sky.it/calcio/fotogallery/2010/02/06/livorno_juventus.html|title=Il fotoracconto di Livorno-Juventus|trans-title=The Livorno-Juventus photo gallery|publisher=[[Sky Sport (Italy)|Sky Sport]]|language=Italian|date=6 February 2010|accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nLegrottaglie was injured during training in late May 2010, and thus missed out on the [[United States]] tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.juventus.com/site/eng/NEWS_newsseriea_33B5B4B1579B41E9B42DA0156E394B5E.asp|title=Juventus land in New York|publisher=Juventus F.C|date=20 May 2010|accessdate=21 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n====Milan====\nOn 31 January 2011, after Juventus signed central defender [[Andrea Barzagli]], the 34-year-old Legrottaglie \u2013 who made just eight appearances in all competitions comprised during the first half of [[2010\u201311 Serie A|the season]], under new manager [[Luigi Delneri]] \u2013 left on a [[Free transfer (association football)|free transfer]] for fellow league side [[A.C. Milan]], signing a six-month deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.juventus.com/site/eng/NEWS_newsseriea_E9ECFAC7927D49668543A6FB21DD457D.asp|title=Legrottaglie joins Milan|publisher=Juventus F.C|date=31 January 2011|accessdate=31 January 2011}}</ref> However, he was only able to make one league appearance for the eventual champions due to a serious head injury suffered during a 0\u20130 draw with [[S.S. Lazio]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=304651&cc=5739|title=Leaders held to stalemate|publisher=ESPN Soccernet|date=1 February 2011|accessdate=1 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/notizie-ultima-ora/Atri_sport/Milan-Bonera-Legrottaglie-ospedale/01-02-2011/2-A_000142260.shtml|title=Milan: Bonera e Legrottaglie in ospedale|trans-title=Milan: Bonera and Legrottaglie in hospital|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=1 February 2011|accessdate=9 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nLegrottaglie was released on 30 June, following the expiration of his contract.\n\n====Catania====\nOn 24 August 2011, Legrottaglie joined [[Calcio Catania]] on a two-year contract. He scored on his official debut, a 3\u20133 away draw against [[Novara Calcio]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/327149?cc=5739|title=Novara 3\u20133 Catania|publisher=ESPN Soccernet|date=2 October 2011|accessdate=4 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nLegrottaglie revived his career overall under [[Vincenzo Montella]]. He finished [[2011\u201312 Serie A|2011\u201312]] with 35 official games and six goals, helping the [[Sicily|Sicilians]] to a fourth successive season in which they broke their record points total in Serie A, finishing 11th.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportmediaset.mediaset.it/calcio/calcioserieA/articoli/78932/legrottaglie-gol-catania-europeo-.shtml|title=Legrottaglie-gol, Catania \"europeo\"|trans-title=Legrottaglie-goal, \"European\" Catania|publisher=Sport Media Set|language=Italian|date=18 March 2012|accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Squadre/Catania/29-03-2012/catania-profumo-d-europa-montella-fabbrica-gol-91768411327.shtml?refresh_ce-cp|title=Catania, profumo d'Europa \u2013 Montella guida il Piccolo Barcellona|trans-title=Catania, scent of Europe \u2013 Montella at the helm of Little Barcelona|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|first=Giovanni|last=Finocchiaro|language=Italian|date=29 March 2012|accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.calcionews24.com/catania-legrottaglie-montella-un-predestinato-229570/|title=Catania, Legrottaglie: \"Montella un predestinato\"|trans-title=Catania, Legrottaglie: \u201cMontella is a natural\u201d|publisher=Calcio News 24|language=Italian|date=28 April 2012|accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/it/news/2/serie-a/2012/05/07/3086561/legrottaglie-catania-amore-che-durer%C3%A0-a-lungo-mi-sono|title=Legrottaglie-Catania, amore che durer\u00e0 a lungo: \"Mi sono trovato benissimo, da qui non mi muovo\"|trans-title=Legrottaglie-Catania, love to last forever: \"I felt terrific, I'm staying put\"|publisher=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|first=Daniele|last=Gamberini|language=Italian|date=7 May 2012|accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===International===\nLegrottaglie made his debut for [[Italy national football team|Italy]] on 20 November 2002, in a [[Exhibition game|friendly match]] with [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]] in [[Pescara]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.italia1910.com/partita.asp?idpartita=608|title=Italia-Turchia (1\u20131)|trans-title=Italy-Turkey (1\u20131)|publisher=Italia 1910|language=Italian|accessdate=12 February 2015}}</ref> and went on to appear in a further six matches in a one-year span, mostly friendlies. He scored his only goal in April 2003, in a 2\u20131 victory over [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]].<ref name=GOAL>{{cite web|url=http://www.italia1910.com/partita.asp?d=30/04/2003|title=Italia-Svizzera (2\u20131)|trans-title=Italy-Switzerland (2\u20131)|publisher=Italia 1910|language=Italian|accessdate=12 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nFollowing solid performances at Juventus, Legrottaglie received his first [[Cap (sport)|cap]] in four years, appearing in a friendly against [[Austria national football team|Austria]] while filling in for injured teammate Chiellini in an 18 August 2008 contest held in [[Nice]]. His former Juventus coach Lippi was in charge of the national team.\n\nOn 2 May 2010, 33-year-old Legrottaglie was included in a 29-man provisional list for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]], attending the training camp in [[Rome]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.figc.it/it/204/24432/2010/05/News.shtml|title=Verso il Mondiale. Ventinove Azzurri convocati per lo stage di Roma|trans-title=Towards the World Cup. Twenty-nine Blues called to training camp in Rome|publisher=[[Italian Football Federation]]|language=Italian|date=2 May 2010|accessdate=11 May 2010|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100505035854/http://www.figc.it/it/204/24432/2010/05/News.shtml|archive-date=5 May 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> but was subsequently dropped from the 30-player list submitted to [[FIFA]] on the 11th, with [[Villarreal CF]]'s [[Giuseppe Rossi]] and [[A.S. Roma]]'s [[Daniele De Rossi]] taking his place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.figc.it/it/204/24545/2010/05/News.shtml|title=Ufficializzata la lista dei 30: C\u2019\u00e8 Giuseppe Rossi al posto di Legrottaglie|trans-title=List of 30 players official: Giuseppe Rossi for Legrottaglie|publisher=Italian Football Federation|language=Italian|date=11 May 2010|accessdate=11 May 2010|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100514144154/http://www.figc.it/it/204/24545/2010/05/News.shtml|archive-date=14 May 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> His only major international tournament was the [[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup]] in [[South Africa]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Nazionale/04-06-2009/santon-sud-africa-50488544529.shtml|title=Santon in Sud Africa \u2013 Pazzini resta fuori|trans-title=Santon in South Africa \u2013 Pazzini remains excluded|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=4 June 2009|accessdate=17 January 2017}}</ref> with Italy exiting in the group stage.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/international/5596826/Confederations-Cup-Brazil-and-Kaka-humiliate-Italy.html|title=Confederations Cup: Brazil and Kaka humiliate Italy|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|first=Duncan|last=White|date=21 June 2009|accessdate=17 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n====International goals====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! # !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1. || 30 April 2003 || [[Geneva]], Switzerland || {{fb|SUI}} || 2\u20131 || Win || [[Exhibition game|Friendly]]<ref name=GOAL/>\n|}\n\n==Coaching career==\nLegrottaglie retired at the end of the [[2013\u201314 Serie A|2013\u201314 campaign]] as Catania suffered top-flight relegation, aged nearly 38. He then returned to Bari after 18 years, being appointed under-17 team manager.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://corrieredelmezzogiorno.corriere.it/bari/notizie/sport/2014/18-luglio-2014/largo-giovani-bari-punta-vivaiolegrottaglie-allenera-allievi-223591450035.shtml|title=Largo ai giovani, il Bari punta sul vivaio Legrottaglie allener\u00e0 gli allievi|trans-title=Make way for the young, Bari focus on academy Legrottaglie will coach the students|newspaper=[[Corriere del Mezzogiorno]]|first=Davide|last=Lattanzi|language=Italian|date=18 July 2014|accessdate=27 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nLegrottaglie took his first role as a head coach in July 2015, accepting an offer from Sicilian [[Lega Pro]] club [[S.S. Akragas Citt\u00e0 dei Templi]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calciomercato/17-07-2015/legrottaglie-riparte-sicilia-sara-allenatore-akragas-120593968701.shtml|title=Legrottaglie riparte dalla Sicilia: sar\u00e0 l'allenatore dell'Akragas|trans-title=Legrottaglie leaves for Sicily: he will be Akragas' coach|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=9 January 2017|accessdate=17 July 2015}}</ref> He resigned the following January due to poor results<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tuttosport.com/news/calcio/calciomercato/2016/01/17-7628064/calciomercato_akragas_legrottaglie_lascia_la_panchina/|title=Calciomercato Akragas, Legrottaglie lascia la panchina|trans-title=Calciomercato Akragas, Legrottaglie leaves the bench|newspaper=[[Tuttosport]]|language=Italian|date=9 January 2017|accessdate=17 January 2016}}</ref> and, on 9 January 2017, was named new assistant to [[Massimo Rastelli]] at [[Cagliari Calcio]] in the [[Italian football league system|Italian top division]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagliaricalcio.com/news/ultimissime/15706/legrottaglie-nello-staff-tecnico-rossoblu|title=Legrottaglie nello staff tecnico rossobl\u00f9|trans-title=Legrottaglie in red-and-blue staff|publisher=Cagliari Calcio|language=Italian|date=9 January 2017|accessdate=9 January 2017}}</ref> in October, as the latter was dismissed, he too left.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagliarinews24.com/legrottaglie-saluta-cagliari-grazie/|title=Legrottaglie saluta Cagliari: \u00abRischi del mestiere, grazie a tutti\u00bb|trans-title=Legrottaglie salutes Cagliari: \u00abGoes with the territory, thanks everybody\u00bb|publisher=Cagliari News 24|first=Sergio|last=Cadeddu|language=Italian|date=17 October 2017|accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 June 2019, Legrottaglie was announced as the new under-19 manager of [[Delfino Pescara 1936]], replacing [[Luciano Zauri]] after the latter's promotion as first-team manager.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ilpescara.it/sport/calcio/nicola-legrottaglie-allenatore-primavera-pescara.html|title=Nicola Legrottaglie nuovo allenatore della Primavera del Pescara|trans-title=Nicola Legrottaglie new Pescara ''Primavera'' manager|newspaper=Il Pescara|language=Italian|date=24 June 2019|accessdate=7 July 2019}}</ref> On 21 January 2020, he was promoted to head coach after Zauri's resignation from his post.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.corrieredellosport.it/news/calcio/serie-b/pescara/2020/01/21-65843497/pescara_panchina_a_legrottaglie_e_ufficiale/|title=Pescara, panchina a Legrottaglie: \u00e8 ufficiale|title=Pescara, Legrottaglie to the bench: it's official|newspaper=[[Corriere dello Sport \u2013 Stadio|Corriere dello Sport]]|language=Italian|date=21 January 2020|accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nLegrottaglie was praised by pundits for his physical attributes and his ability in the air, making him a goal threat from set pieces.<ref name=Juventinologo>{{cite web|url=http://juventinologo.blogspot.ca/2009/04/nicola-legrottaglie-scheda-tecnica.html|title=Nicola Legrottaglie \u2013 Scheda tecnica|trans-title=Nicola Legrottaglie \u2013 Technical report|publisher=Juventinologo|language=Italian|date=16 April 2009|accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref> A strong yet elegant player, he excelled in sliding challenges and at organising high defensive lines, also being gifted with good technical ability, passing range and vision, which allowed him to advance into the midfield. He was also tactically versatile, excelling at reading the game and possessing a powerful shot from distance.\n\nDespite his reputation, Legrottaglie was also criticised at times for inconsistency and lapses in man-marking.<ref name=Juventinologo/>\n\n==Personal life==\nLegrottaglie attracted controversy when he came out strongly against [[homosexuality]], calling it a \"sin\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/10/italy/2009/03/18/1161761/nicola-legrottaglie-insists-homosexuality-is-a-sin|title=Nicola Legrottaglie insists 'homosexuality is a sin'|publisher=Goal|first=Salvatore|last=Landolina|date=18 March 2009|accessdate=18 March 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n'''Juventus'''<ref name=SW>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/coaches/nicola-legrottaglie/17687/|title=N. Legrottaglie \u2013 Trophies|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=21 December 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Supercoppa Italiana]]: [[2003 Supercoppa Italiana|2003]]\n*[[Serie B]]: [[2006\u201307 Serie B|2006\u201307]]\n*[[Coppa Italia]] runner-up: [[2004 Coppa Italia Final|2003\u201304]]\n\n'''Milan'''<ref name=SW/>\n*[[Serie A]]: [[2010\u201311 Serie A|2010\u201311]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081217140125/https://www.juventus.com/site/ita/TAS_schedagiocatoreprimasquadra_417D659ABA15488388474BCB517B9004.asp Juventus official profile] {{in lang|it}}\n*{{TuttoCalciatori|Legrottaglie_Nicola}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120829155902/http://www.figc.it/nazionali/DettaglioConvocato?codiceConvocato=1524&squadra=1 National team data] {{in lang|it}} {{dead link|date=March 2019}}\n*{{NFT player|3373}}\n\n{{Italy Squad 2009 FIFA Confederations Cup}}\n{{Delfino Pescara 1936 squad}}\n{{Serie B managers}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Legrottaglie, Nicola}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Taranto]]\n[[Category:Italian Protestants]]\n[[Category:Italian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Serie B players]]\n[[Category:Serie C players]]\n[[Category:S.S.C. Bari players]]\n[[Category:U.S. Pistoiese 1921 players]]\n[[Category:A.C. Prato players]]\n[[Category:A.C. ChievoVerona players]]\n[[Category:Reggio Audace F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Modena F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Juventus F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bologna F.C. 1909 players]]\n[[Category:Robur Siena players]]\n[[Category:A.C. Milan players]]\n[[Category:Calcio Catania players]]\n[[Category:Italy international footballers]]\n[[Category:2009 FIFA Confederations Cup players]]\n[[Category:Italian football managers]]\n[[Category:Serie B managers]]\n[[Category:Delfino Pescara 1936 managers]]\n", "name_user": "Quite A Character", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCoaching career:My bad while arranging ref.", "url_page":