{"title_page": "Kai Havertz", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Kai Havertz\n| fullname = \n| image = Kai-Havertz-August-2018.jpg\n| caption = Havertz with Bayer Leverkusen in 2018\n| height = 1.89m<ref>https://www.bayer04.de/de-de/player/werkself/bayer-04-leverkusen/kai-havertz</ref>\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1999|6|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Aachen]], Germany\n| position = [[Attacking Midfielder]]/[[Winger (association football)|Winger]]\n| currentclub = [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]]\n| clubnumber = 29\n| youthyears1 = 2003\u20132009\n| youthclubs1 = Alemannia Mariadorf\n| youthyears2 = 2009\u20132010\n| youthclubs2 = [[Alemannia Aachen]]\n| youthyears3 = 2010\u20132017\n| youthclubs3 = [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]]\n| years1 = 2016\u2013\n| clubs1 = [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]]\n| caps1 = 110\n| goals1 = 30\n| nationalyears1 = 2014\u20132015\n| nationalteam1 = [[Germany national under-16 football team|Germany U16]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 6\n| nationalgoals1 = 2\n| nationalyears2 = 2015\u20132016\n| nationalteam2 = [[Germany national under-17 football team|Germany U17]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 16\n| nationalgoals2 = 7\n| nationalyears3 = 2017\u20132018\n| nationalteam3 = [[Germany national under-19 football team|Germany U19]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 8\n| nationalgoals3 = 7\n| nationalyears4 = 2018\u2013\n| nationalteam4 = [[Germany national football team|Germany]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 7\n| nationalgoals4 = 1\n| pcupdate = 16:31, 7 March 2020 (UTC)\n| ntupdate = 20:40, 13 October 2019 (UTC)\n}}\n\n'''Kai Havertz''' (born 11 June 1999) is a German professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as an [[midfielder|attacking midfielder]] or [[Forward (association football)#Winger|right winger]] for [[Bundesliga]] side [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]] and the [[Germany national football team|German national team]].\n\nUpon making his debut for Leverkusen in 2016, Havertz became the club's youngest ever debutant in the [[Bundesliga]] and he became their youngest ever goalscorer when he scored his first goal the following year. He is also the youngest player to reach the milestones of 50 and 100 league appearances in the German top-flight. The future holds so much for this young talent who is being tipped for big money moves.\n\n==Club career==\n===Youth career===\nBorn in [[Aachen]], Germany, Havertz received his first experience in football with amateur side Alemannia Mariadorf. In 2008, he was signed by [[2. Bundesliga|second division]] side [[Alemannia Aachen]] where he spent two years in the club's academy before joining Bayer Leverkusen at the age of 11.<ref name=UEFA>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2435364.html|title=UEFA.com's weekly wonderkid: Kai Havertz|website=UEFA|last=R\u00f6ber|first=Philip|date=4 February 2017|accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref> In 2016, after scoring 18 goals for the club's U-17 side, he was awarded the silver U-17 [[Fritz Walter Medal]] before breaking into Leverkusen's senior side the following year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/bravertz-julian-brandt-kai-havertz-bayer-leverkusen-s-german-midfield-core-3039|title=Bravertz: Julian Brandt and Kai Havertz forming Bayer Leverkusen\u2019s German midfield core|publisher=Bundesliga|date=15 March 2019|accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vavel.com/en/international-football/germany-bundesliga/747042-bayer-leverkusens-overlooked-youth-prospects.html|title=Bayer Leverkusen's overlooked youth prospects|website=Vavel|last=McGuiness|first=Kev|date=25 January 2017|accessdate=6 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Bayer Leverkusen===\nHavertz made his debut for Bayer Leverkusen on 15 October 2016, coming on as a second-half [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] for [[Charles Ar\u00e1nguiz]] in a 2\u20131 Bundesliga loss to [[SV Werder Bremen|Werder Bremen]]. Upon entering the field of play, he became the club's youngest ever Bundesliga debutant at the age of 17 years and 126 days.<ref name=UEFA/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2016/10/15/germany/bundesliga/sv-werder-bremen/bayer-04-leverkusen/2254966/|title=Werder Bremen v Bayer Leverkusen|website=Soccerway|date=15 October 2016|accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref> On 17 February 2017, he [[Assist (football)|assisted]] teammate [[Karim Bellarabi]] to score the 50 000th Bundesliga goal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2692716-european-golden-boys-xi-dembele-and-havertz-continue-to-shine-bright|title=European Golden Boys XI: Dembele and Havertz continue to shine brightly|website=Bleacher Report|date=21 February 2017|accessdate=6 April 2017}}</ref> Four days later, following the suspension of teammate [[Hakan \u00c7alhano\u011flu]], he was handed his first [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] start in the first leg of a round of 16 loss to [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sbnation.com/soccer/2017/2/21/14688402/bayer-leverkusen-vs-atletico-madrid-champions-league-2017-lineups-team-news |title=Bayer Leverkusen vs. Atl\u00e9tico Madrid lineups: Bayer hand teenager Havertz first Champions League start |website=SBNation|publisher=Jack Sargeant |access-date=21 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/person-interest-german-wunderkind-kai-havertz-one-watch/|title=Person of Interest: German wunderkind Kai Havertz one to watch|website=Sports Net|last=Molinaro|first=John|date=14 March 2017|accessdate=5 April 2017}}</ref> He was ruled out of the return leg of the fixture in March, however, as the match clashed with the examinations period at his school.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/blog/the-toe-poke/65/post/3082292/bayer-leverkusen-starlet-kai-havertz-ruled-out-for-school-exam|title=Bayer Leverkusen starlet ruled out for school exam|website=ESPN|last=Wright|first=Chris|date=14 March 2017|accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club on 2 April, netting a later equalizer in a 3\u20133 draw with [[VfL Wolfsburg]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njherald.com/article/20170402/AP/304029868|title=Gomez hat trick but Wolfsburg held 3\u20133 at Leverkusen|website=New Jersey Herald|last=Fahey|first=Ciaran|date=2 April 2017|accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref> Upon doing so, Havertz broke another club record to become Leverkusen's youngest-ever goalscorer in the Bundesliga at the age of 17.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/blmd26n-rising-star-bayer-leverkusen-kai-havertz-goalmania-439148.jsp|title=Rising Star: Bayer Leverkusen's Kai Havertz|website=Bundesliga|last=Gladwell|first=Ben|date=2 April 2017|accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref> He ultimately made 28 appearances across all competitions and scored four goals, including a brace against [[Hertha BSC]] on the final day of the season, as Leverkusen ended the campaign in 12th position.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dewezet.de/startseite_artikel,-hertha-trotz-26-gegen-bayer-kurz-vor-europa-_arid,2373396.html|title=Hertha trotz 2:6 gegen Bayer kurz vor Europa|website=Dewezet|last1=Mende|last2=Kr\u1e7bhler|first1=Jens|first2=Andreas|date=20 May 2017|accessdate=20 May 2017}}{{in lang|de}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 April 2018, Havertz became the youngest player in the history of the Bundesliga to reach 50 appearances at 18 years and 307 days old, breaking the record previously held by [[Timo Werner]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/bayer-leverkusen-s-kai-havertz-part-ozil-part-ballack-454810.jsp |title=Bayer Leverkusen's Kai Havertz becomes youngest player in history to reach 50 appearances |website=Bundesliga|publisher=[[Deutsche Fu\u00dfball Liga]] |date=14 April 2018 |access-date=14 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Bayer-leverkusen-record-de-precocite-pour-kai-havertz/892785|title=Bayer Leverkusen : record de pr\u00e9cocit\u00e9 pour Kai Havertz|publisher=LEquipe|date=14 April 2018|accessdate=15 April 2018|language=French}}</ref> He went on to end his second full campaign with the club with 30 league appearances and three goals to his name as Leverkusen ended the season in fifth place.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/kai-havertz-bayer-leverkusen-teen-targets-germany-call-up-julian-brandt-511182.jsp|title=Bayer Leverkusen's Kai Havertz: \"I should be aiming for the Germany national team\"|publisher=Bundesliga|date=24 August 2018|accessdate=2 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nHavertz continued to impress during the following season, despite Leverkusen initially struggling in the league, and by the mid-way point of the campaign was the only player to have started every match for the club, scoring six goals along the way.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/bayer-leverkusen-hertha-berlin-live-line-ups-stats-kai-havertz-leon-bailey-fantasy-1046|title=Bayer Leverkusen up to 9th after Kai Havertz-inspired win over Hertha Berlin|publisher=Bundesliga|date=24 December 2018|accessdate=26 December 2018}}</ref> On 26 January 2019, he became Leverkusen's youngest-ever [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty]] scorer when he scored from the spot in a 3\u20130 league win over Wolfsburg, aged 19 years, seven months and 16 days.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/wolfsburg-bayer-leverkusen-live-line-ups-stats-leon-bailey-havertz-john-brooks-3034-1757|title=Kai Havertz, Kevin Volland and Julian Brandt fire Bayer Leverkusen past Wolfsburg|publisher=Bundesliga|date=27 January 2019|accessdate=27 January 2019}}</ref>\nThe following month, he became the second youngest-ever player to achieve 75 Bundesliga appearances, behind [[Julian Draxler]], when he started and scored in a 2\u20130 win over [[Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/bayer-leverkusen-fortuna-dusseldorf-live-line-ups-stats-leon-bailey-havertz-lukebakio-3331-2350|title=Kai Havertz and Leon Bailey fire Bayer Leverkusen to victory over Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf|publisher=Bundesliga|date=17 February 2019|accessdate=18 February 2019}}</ref> On 13 April, he scored on his 100th appearance for Leverkusen to help the club to a 1\u20130 league win over [[VfB Stuttgart|Stuttgart]]. The goal, his 13th for the campaign, also saw him become the youngest player since Stuttgart's own [[Horst K\u00f6ppel]] in [[1967\u201368 Bundesliga|1967\u201368]] to score 13 goals in a single league season.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/vfb-stuttgart-bayer-leverkusen-live-line-ups-stats-leon-bailey-pavard-gomez-3628|title=Kai Havertz scores on 100th appearance as Bayer Leverkusen down VfB Stuttgart|publisher=Bundesliga|date=13 April 2019|accessdate=14 April 2019}}</ref> On 5 May, he scored his 15th goal of the campaign during a 6\u20131 win over [[Eintracht Frankfurt]]; a match which for the first time ever saw seven goals scored in the first half of a Bundesliga match.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/bayer-leverkusen-eintracht-frankfurt-live-line-ups-stats-luka-jovic-havertz-4195|title=Kai Havertz on target again as Bayer Leverkusen smash six past Eintracht Frankfurt in record-breaking game|publisher=Bundesliga|date=5 May 2019|accessdate=6 May 2019}}</ref> On the final day of the season, he became the highest scoring teenager in a single Bundesliga campaign when he scored his 17th goal during a 5\u20131 win over [[Hertha BSC]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Kai Havertz, Lucas Alario and Julian Brandt secure Champions League spot for Bayer Leverkusen|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/hertha-berlin-bayer-leverkusen-live-line-ups-stats-brandt-havertz-bailey-kalou-4490|publisher=Bundesliga|date=18 May 2019|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> At the end of the season, he was named runner-up to [[Marco Reus]] for the [[Footballer of the Year in Germany|German Footballer of the Year]] award, losing out by just 37 votes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/marco-reus-named-footballer-of-the-year-2019-borussia-dortmund-5839|title=Borussia Dortmund captain Marco Reus named Germany's Footballer of the Year 2019|publisher=Bundesliga|date=29 July 2019|accessdate=1 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn the opening day of the [[2019\u201320 Bundesliga|2019\u201320 campaign]], Havertz scored in Leverkusen's 3\u20132 win over [[SC Paderborn 07|Paderborn]], becoming the second-youngest player of all-time behind K\u00f6ppel to score 25 Bundesliga goals.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/bayer-leverkusen-paderborn-live-line-ups-stats-havertz-bailey-jonathan-tah-6196|title=Kai Havertz makes history as Bayer Leverkusen overcome new boys Paderborn\n|publisher=Bundesliga|date=18 August 2019|accessdate=19 August 2019}}</ref> In December, at the age of 20 years, six months and four days, he broke another of Werner's record to become the youngest-ever player to reach 100 Bundesliga appearances when he started in his side's 2\u20130 defeat to Koln.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/kai-havertz-100-bundesliga-appearances-for-bayer-leverkusen-at-20-8688|title=Kai Havertz: 100 Bundesliga appearances for Bayer Leverkusen at 20|publisher=Bundesliga|date=15 December 2019|accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:2019-06-11 Fu\u00dfball, M\u00e4nner, L\u00e4nderspiel, Deutschland-Estland StP 2059 LR10 by Stepro.jpg|thumb|Havertz (pictured during [[Germany national football team|Germany]]'s 8\u20130 win over [[Estonia national football team|Estonia]] in June 2019) made his senior debut nine months earlier against [[Peru national football team|Peru]].]]\n\n===Youth===\nHavertz made his debut for the [[Germany national under-16 football team|Germany national under-16 team]] on 11 November 2014, starting in the friendly match against the [[Czech Republic national under-16 football team|Czech Republic]] before being substituted out in the 57th minute for [[Tom Baack]]. The match finished as a 3\u20131 win for Germany.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dfb.de/datencenter/laenderspiel-2512/2014-2015/saison/2215057 |title=U 16 L\u00e4nderspiel: Tschechische Republik \u2013 Deutschland |trans-title=Under-16 international: Czech Republic \u2013 Germany |website=DFB.de |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |date=11 November 2014 |access-date=29 August 2018 |language=German}}</ref>\n\nHavertz was included in [[2016 UEFA European Under-17 Championship squads#Germany|Germany's squad]] for the [[2016 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]] in Azerbaijan.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dfb.de/news/detail/u-17-em-unser-team-fuer-aserbaidschan-145326/full/1/ |title=U 17-EM: Unser Team f\u00fcr Aserbaidschan |trans-title=European Under-17 Championship: Our team for Azerbaijan |website=DFB.de |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |date=4 May 2016 |access-date=29 August 2018 |language=German}}</ref> He appeared in all five of Germany's matches, scoring once before Germany were eliminated by [[Spain national under-17 football team|Spain]] in the semi-finals.\n\nFollowing a 15-month absence from youth internationals, Havertz made his debut for [[Germany national under-19 football team|Germany's under-19 team]], debuting on 31 August 2017 in the 0\u20130 friendly draw against [[Switzerland national under-19 football team|Switzerland]], coming on in the 72nd minute for [[Palk\u00f3 D\u00e1rdai]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dfb.de/datencenter/laenderspiel-1355/2017-2018/saison/2258210 |title=U 19 L\u00e4nderspiel: Schweiz \u2013 Deutschland |trans-title=Under-19 international: Switzerland \u2013 Germany |website=DFB.de |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |date=31 August 2017 |access-date=29 August 2018 |language=German}}</ref> On 4 October 2017, in his third appearance for the under-19 team, Havertz scored four goals in a 5\u20131 win against [[Belarus national football team|Belarus]] in the first round of [[2018 UEFA European Under-19 Championship qualification|European Under-19 Championship qualifying]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dfb.de/datencenter/em-qualifikation-1231/2017-2018/gruppe-2/2258228 |title=U 19 EM Qualifikation: Deutschland \u2013 Wei\u00dfrussland |trans-title=Under-19 Euro qualification: Germany \u2013 Belarus |website=DFB.de |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |date=4 October 2017 |access-date=29 August 2018 |language=German}}</ref> He was later named captain of the under-19 side.<ref name=fcu>{{cite news|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/kai-havertz-leroy-sane-germany-squad-france-uefa-nations-league-511492.jsp|title=Kai Havertz receives maiden Germany call-up for UEFA Nations League opener with France|publisher=Bundesliga|date=30 August 2018|accessdate=30 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Senior===\nOn 29 August 2018, Havertz was called up to [[Germany national football team|Germany's senior team]] for the first time by head coach [[Joachim L\u00f6w]]. He was included in the squad for Germany's [[2018\u201319 UEFA Nations League|UEFA Nations League]] match against [[France national football team|France]] and friendly against [[Peru national football team|Peru]].<ref name=fcu/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dfb.de/news/detail/nations-league-drei-neue-drei-rueckkehrer-191761/ |title=Nations League: Drei Neue, drei R\u00fcckkehrer |trans-title=Nations League: Three new players, three returnees |website=DFB.de |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |date=29 August 2018 |access-date=29 August 2018 |language=German}}</ref> Havertz made his international debut on 9 September 2018, coming on as a substitute in the 88th minute for [[Timo Werner]] against Peru, with the match finishing as a 2\u20131 home win for Germany.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/nationalelf/startseite/fussball-nationalteams-freundschaftsspiele/2018/5/4212631/spielbericht_deutschland_peru.html |title=Erstes Spiel, erstes Tor: Deb\u00fctant Schulz trifft zum Sieg |trans-title=First match, first goal: debutant Schulz scores for victory |website=kicker.de |publisher=[[Kicker (sports magazine)|kicker-sportmagazin]] |date=9 September 2018 |access-date=10 September 2018 |language=German}}</ref> Upon making his debut, he became the first player born in 1999 to represent the national team.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=2590311.html|title=Scout Report: Leverkusen midfielder Kai Havertz|publisher=UEFA|date=20 February 2019|accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nHavertz has been described as technically-gifted, two-footed midfielder who is comfortable with the ball on either foot and adept with his head.<ref name=desc>{{cite news|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/kai-havertz-becoming-bayer-leverkusen-real-deal-513972.jsp|title=Kai Havertz becoming the real deal at Bayer Leverkusen|publisher=Bundesliga|date=15 October 2018|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> During his formative years, his style of play drew early comparisons to compatriot [[Mesut \u00d6zil]], with Havertz himself admitting the [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] midfielder was a player he looked up to.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.welt.de/sport/fussball/bundesliga/bayer-leverkusen/article162224749/Dieser-17-Jaehrige-gilt-als-Deutschlands-neuer-Oezil.html|title=Dieser 17-J\u00e4hrige gilt als Deutschlands neuer \u00d6zil|website=Welt|last=Wallrodt|first=Lars|date=21 February 2017|accessdate=6 April 2017}}{{in lang|de}}</ref> By the age of 19, and following numerous impressive performances in the Bundesliga, further comparisons had been drawn between Havertz and former Leverkusen players such as [[Michael Ballack]], [[Toni Kroos]] and [[Arturo Vidal]], and German media began describing him as a combination of the lot and an ''Allesk\u00f6nner'' \u2013 a player who can do everything.<ref name=desc/>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\n{{updated|12 March 2020|<ref>{{cite web|title=Kai Havertz Socceway Profile|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/kai-havertz/440864/|accessdate=21 February 2017}}</ref>}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup{{efn|Includes [[DFB-Pokal]]}}\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]]\n|[[2016\u201317 Bayer 04 Leverkusen season|2016\u201317]]\n|[[Bundesliga]]\n|24||4||1||0||3{{efn|name=UCL|Appearance(s) in [[UEFA Champions League]]}}||0||28||4\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 Bayer 04 Leverkusen season|2017\u201318]]\n|Bundesliga\n|30||3||5||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||35||4\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Bayer 04 Leverkusen season|2018\u201319]]\n|Bundesliga\n|34||17||2||0||6{{efn|name=UEL|Appearance(s) in [[UEFA Europa League]]}}||3||42||20\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 Bayer 04 Leverkusen season|2019\u201320]]\n|Bundesliga\n|22||6||4||1||8{{efn|Five appearances in [[UEFA Champions League]], three appearance and three goals in [[UEFA Europa League]]}}||3||34||10\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Totals!!110!!30!!12!!2!!17!!6!!139!!38\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career totals!!110!!30!!12!!2!!17!!6!!139!!38\n|}\n'''Notes'''\n{{Notelist}}\n\n===International===\n{{updated|13 October 2019|<ref>{{NFT player|71914}}</ref>}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|[[Germany national football team|Germany]]\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|2018||2||0\n|-\n|2019||5||1\n|-\n!Total!!7!!1\n|}\n\n====International goals====\n:''Scores and results list Germany's goal tally first.''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! # !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1 || 9 October 2019 || [[Signal Iduna Park]], [[Dortmund]], Germany || {{fb|ARG}} || align=center | '''2'''\u20130 || align=center | 2\u20132 || [[Exhibition game#Association football|Friendly]]\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===Individual===\n'''Medals'''\n* [[Fritz Walter Medal]]: U17 Silver - 2016<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dfb.de/news/detail/fritz-walter-medaille-fuer-ehegoetz-henrichs-und-itter-151343/ |title=Fritz-Walter-Medaille f\u00fcr Eheg\u00f6tz, Henrichs und Itter |trans-title=Fritz Walter Medal for Eheg\u00f6tz, Henrichs and Itter |website=DFB.de |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |date=8 August 2016 |access-date=29 August 2018 |language=German}}</ref>\n* [[Fritz Walter Medal]]: U19 Gold - 2018<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dfb.de/news/detail/fritz-walter-medaille-in-gold-an-havertz-katterbach-und-pawollek-190126/ |title=Fritz-Walter-Medaille in Gold an Havertz, Katterbach und Pawollek |trans-title=Fritz Walter medal in gold for Havertz, Katterbach and Pawollek |website=DFB.de |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |date=24 July 2018 |access-date=29 August 2018 |language=German}}</ref>\n\n'''Other'''\n* [[Bundesliga]] Team of the Year: [[2018\u201319 Bundesliga|2018\u201319]]<ref>{{cite web | url = https://tots.bundesliga.com/en/ | title = This is the Team of the season 2018/19 | publisher = bundesliga.com | date = 27 May 2019 | accessdate = 30 October 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Bundesliga]] Player of the Month: [[2018\u201319 Bundesliga|April 2019]], May 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/player-of-the-month-2018-19-ea-sports-fifa-19-2583-803|title=Bayer Leverkusen's Kai Havertz wins Bundesliga Player of the Month for May!|last=|first=|date=May 2019|website=Bundesliga|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n*[[UEFA Champions League]] Breakthrough XI: 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2635905.html|title=Champions League breakthrough team of 2019|last=|first=|date=30 December 2019|website=UEFA.com|publisher=UEFA.com Reporters & Editors|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{WorldFootball.net}}\n*{{Soccerway}}\n*{{UEFA player}}\n*{{DFB|350659<!-- kai-havertz -->}}\n*{{Kicker|<!-- havertz-kai- -->86141}}\n\n{{Bayer 04 Leverkusen squad}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards\n|bg = gold\n|fg = navy\n|list1 =\n{{Fritz Walter Medal Under-17}}\n{{Fritz Walter Medal Under-19}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Havertz, Kai}}\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Aachen]]\n[[Category:Footballers from North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n[[Category:German footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Bayer 04 Leverkusen players]]\n[[Category:Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:Germany youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Germany international footballers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Kai Havertz\n| fullname = \n| image = Kai-Havertz-August-2018.jpg\n| caption = Havertz with Bayer Leverkusen in 2018\n| height = 1.89m<ref>https://www.bayer04.de/de-de/player/werkself/bayer-04-leverkusen/kai-havertz</ref>\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1999|6|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Aachen]], Germany\n| position = [[Attacking Midfielder]]/[[Winger (association football)|Winger]]\n| currentclub = [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]]\n| clubnumber = 29\n| youthyears1 = 2003\u20132009\n| youthclubs1 = Alemannia Mariadorf\n| youthyears2 = 2009\u20132010\n| youthclubs2 = [[Alemannia Aachen]]\n| youthyears3 = 2010\u20132017\n| youthclubs3 = [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]]\n| years1 = 2016\u2013\n| clubs1 = [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]]\n| caps1 = 110\n| goals1 = 30\n| nationalyears1 = 2014\u20132015\n| nationalteam1 = [[Germany national under-16 football team|Germany U16]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 6\n| nationalgoals1 = 2\n| nationalyears2 = 2015\u20132016\n| nationalteam2 = [[Germany national under-17 football team|Germany U17]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 16\n| nationalgoals2 = 7\n| nationalyears3 = 2017\u20132018\n| nationalteam3 = [[Germany national under-19 football team|Germany U19]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 8\n| nationalgoals3 = 7\n| nationalyears4 = 2018\u2013\n| nationalteam4 = [[Germany national football team|Germany]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 7\n| nationalgoals4 = 1\n| pcupdate = 16:31, 7 March 2020 (UTC)\n| ntupdate = 20:40, 13 October 2019 (UTC)\n}}\n\n'''Kai Havertz''' (born 11 June 1999) is a German professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as an [[midfielder|attacking midfielder]] or [[Forward (association football)#Winger|right winger]] for [[Bundesliga]] side [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]] and the [[Germany national football team|German national team]].\n\nUpon making his debut for Leverkusen in 2016, Havertz became the club's youngest ever debutant in the [[Bundesliga]] and he became their youngest ever goalscorer when he scored his first goal the following year. He is also the youngest player to reach the milestones of 50 and 100 league appearances in the German top-flight.\n\n==Club career==\n===Youth career===\nBorn in [[Aachen]], Germany, Havertz received his first experience in football with amateur side Alemannia Mariadorf. In 2008, he was signed by [[2. Bundesliga|second division]] side [[Alemannia Aachen]] where he spent two years in the club's academy before joining Bayer Leverkusen at the age of 11.<ref name=UEFA>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2435364.html|title=UEFA.com's weekly wonderkid: Kai Havertz|website=UEFA|last=R\u00f6ber|first=Philip|date=4 February 2017|accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref> In 2016, after scoring 18 goals for the club's U-17 side, he was awarded the silver U-17 [[Fritz Walter Medal]] before breaking into Leverkusen's senior side the following year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/bravertz-julian-brandt-kai-havertz-bayer-leverkusen-s-german-midfield-core-3039|title=Bravertz: Julian Brandt and Kai Havertz forming Bayer Leverkusen\u2019s German midfield core|publisher=Bundesliga|date=15 March 2019|accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vavel.com/en/international-football/germany-bundesliga/747042-bayer-leverkusens-overlooked-youth-prospects.html|title=Bayer Leverkusen's overlooked youth prospects|website=Vavel|last=McGuiness|first=Kev|date=25 January 2017|accessdate=6 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Bayer Leverkusen===\nHavertz made his debut for Bayer Leverkusen on 15 October 2016, coming on as a second-half [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] for [[Charles Ar\u00e1nguiz]] in a 2\u20131 Bundesliga loss to [[SV Werder Bremen|Werder Bremen]]. Upon entering the field of play, he became the club's youngest ever Bundesliga debutant at the age of 17 years and 126 days.<ref name=UEFA/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2016/10/15/germany/bundesliga/sv-werder-bremen/bayer-04-leverkusen/2254966/|title=Werder Bremen v Bayer Leverkusen|website=Soccerway|date=15 October 2016|accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref> On 17 February 2017, he [[Assist (football)|assisted]] teammate [[Karim Bellarabi]] to score the 50 000th Bundesliga goal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2692716-european-golden-boys-xi-dembele-and-havertz-continue-to-shine-bright|title=European Golden Boys XI: Dembele and Havertz continue to shine brightly|website=Bleacher Report|date=21 February 2017|accessdate=6 April 2017}}</ref> Four days later, following the suspension of teammate [[Hakan \u00c7alhano\u011flu]], he was handed his first [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] start in the first leg of a round of 16 loss to [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sbnation.com/soccer/2017/2/21/14688402/bayer-leverkusen-vs-atletico-madrid-champions-league-2017-lineups-team-news |title=Bayer Leverkusen vs. Atl\u00e9tico Madrid lineups: Bayer hand teenager Havertz first Champions League start |website=SBNation|publisher=Jack Sargeant |access-date=21 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/person-interest-german-wunderkind-kai-havertz-one-watch/|title=Person of Interest: German wunderkind Kai Havertz one to watch|website=Sports Net|last=Molinaro|first=John|date=14 March 2017|accessdate=5 April 2017}}</ref> He was ruled out of the return leg of the fixture in March, however, as the match clashed with the examinations period at his school.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/blog/the-toe-poke/65/post/3082292/bayer-leverkusen-starlet-kai-havertz-ruled-out-for-school-exam|title=Bayer Leverkusen starlet ruled out for school exam|website=ESPN|last=Wright|first=Chris|date=14 March 2017|accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club on 2 April, netting a later equalizer in a 3\u20133 draw with [[VfL Wolfsburg]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njherald.com/article/20170402/AP/304029868|title=Gomez hat trick but Wolfsburg held 3\u20133 at Leverkusen|website=New Jersey Herald|last=Fahey|first=Ciaran|date=2 April 2017|accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref> Upon doing so, Havertz broke another club record to become Leverkusen's youngest-ever goalscorer in the Bundesliga at the age of 17.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/blmd26n-rising-star-bayer-leverkusen-kai-havertz-goalmania-439148.jsp|title=Rising Star: Bayer Leverkusen's Kai Havertz|website=Bundesliga|last=Gladwell|first=Ben|date=2 April 2017|accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref> He ultimately made 28 appearances across all competitions and scored four goals, including a brace against [[Hertha BSC]] on the final day of the season, as Leverkusen ended the campaign in 12th position.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dewezet.de/startseite_artikel,-hertha-trotz-26-gegen-bayer-kurz-vor-europa-_arid,2373396.html|title=Hertha trotz 2:6 gegen Bayer kurz vor Europa|website=Dewezet|last1=Mende|last2=Kr\u1e7bhler|first1=Jens|first2=Andreas|date=20 May 2017|accessdate=20 May 2017}}{{in lang|de}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 April 2018, Havertz became the youngest player in the history of the Bundesliga to reach 50 appearances at 18 years and 307 days old, breaking the record previously held by [[Timo Werner]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/bayer-leverkusen-s-kai-havertz-part-ozil-part-ballack-454810.jsp |title=Bayer Leverkusen's Kai Havertz becomes youngest player in history to reach 50 appearances |website=Bundesliga|publisher=[[Deutsche Fu\u00dfball Liga]] |date=14 April 2018 |access-date=14 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Bayer-leverkusen-record-de-precocite-pour-kai-havertz/892785|title=Bayer Leverkusen : record de pr\u00e9cocit\u00e9 pour Kai Havertz|publisher=LEquipe|date=14 April 2018|accessdate=15 April 2018|language=French}}</ref> He went on to end his second full campaign with the club with 30 league appearances and three goals to his name as Leverkusen ended the season in fifth place.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/kai-havertz-bayer-leverkusen-teen-targets-germany-call-up-julian-brandt-511182.jsp|title=Bayer Leverkusen's Kai Havertz: \"I should be aiming for the Germany national team\"|publisher=Bundesliga|date=24 August 2018|accessdate=2 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nHavertz continued to impress during the following season, despite Leverkusen initially struggling in the league, and by the mid-way point of the campaign was the only player to have started every match for the club, scoring six goals along the way.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/bayer-leverkusen-hertha-berlin-live-line-ups-stats-kai-havertz-leon-bailey-fantasy-1046|title=Bayer Leverkusen up to 9th after Kai Havertz-inspired win over Hertha Berlin|publisher=Bundesliga|date=24 December 2018|accessdate=26 December 2018}}</ref> On 26 January 2019, he became Leverkusen's youngest-ever [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty]] scorer when he scored from the spot in a 3\u20130 league win over Wolfsburg, aged 19 years, seven months and 16 days.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/wolfsburg-bayer-leverkusen-live-line-ups-stats-leon-bailey-havertz-john-brooks-3034-1757|title=Kai Havertz, Kevin Volland and Julian Brandt fire Bayer Leverkusen past Wolfsburg|publisher=Bundesliga|date=27 January 2019|accessdate=27 January 2019}}</ref>\nThe following month, he became the second youngest-ever player to achieve 75 Bundesliga appearances, behind [[Julian Draxler]], when he started and scored in a 2\u20130 win over [[Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/bayer-leverkusen-fortuna-dusseldorf-live-line-ups-stats-leon-bailey-havertz-lukebakio-3331-2350|title=Kai Havertz and Leon Bailey fire Bayer Leverkusen to victory over Fortuna D\u00fcsseldorf|publisher=Bundesliga|date=17 February 2019|accessdate=18 February 2019}}</ref> On 13 April, he scored on his 100th appearance for Leverkusen to help the club to a 1\u20130 league win over [[VfB Stuttgart|Stuttgart]]. The goal, his 13th for the campaign, also saw him become the youngest player since Stuttgart's own [[Horst K\u00f6ppel]] in [[1967\u201368 Bundesliga|1967\u201368]] to score 13 goals in a single league season.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/vfb-stuttgart-bayer-leverkusen-live-line-ups-stats-leon-bailey-pavard-gomez-3628|title=Kai Havertz scores on 100th appearance as Bayer Leverkusen down VfB Stuttgart|publisher=Bundesliga|date=13 April 2019|accessdate=14 April 2019}}</ref> On 5 May, he scored his 15th goal of the campaign during a 6\u20131 win over [[Eintracht Frankfurt]]; a match which for the first time ever saw seven goals scored in the first half of a Bundesliga match.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/bayer-leverkusen-eintracht-frankfurt-live-line-ups-stats-luka-jovic-havertz-4195|title=Kai Havertz on target again as Bayer Leverkusen smash six past Eintracht Frankfurt in record-breaking game|publisher=Bundesliga|date=5 May 2019|accessdate=6 May 2019}}</ref> On the final day of the season, he became the highest scoring teenager in a single Bundesliga campaign when he scored his 17th goal during a 5\u20131 win over [[Hertha BSC]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Kai Havertz, Lucas Alario and Julian Brandt secure Champions League spot for Bayer Leverkusen|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/hertha-berlin-bayer-leverkusen-live-line-ups-stats-brandt-havertz-bailey-kalou-4490|publisher=Bundesliga|date=18 May 2019|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> At the end of the season, he was named runner-up to [[Marco Reus]] for the [[Footballer of the Year in Germany|German Footballer of the Year]] award, losing out by just 37 votes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/marco-reus-named-footballer-of-the-year-2019-borussia-dortmund-5839|title=Borussia Dortmund captain Marco Reus named Germany's Footballer of the Year 2019|publisher=Bundesliga|date=29 July 2019|accessdate=1 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn the opening day of the [[2019\u201320 Bundesliga|2019\u201320 campaign]], Havertz scored in Leverkusen's 3\u20132 win over [[SC Paderborn 07|Paderborn]], becoming the second-youngest player of all-time behind K\u00f6ppel to score 25 Bundesliga goals.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/bayer-leverkusen-paderborn-live-line-ups-stats-havertz-bailey-jonathan-tah-6196|title=Kai Havertz makes history as Bayer Leverkusen overcome new boys Paderborn\n|publisher=Bundesliga|date=18 August 2019|accessdate=19 August 2019}}</ref> In December, at the age of 20 years, six months and four days, he broke another of Werner's record to become the youngest-ever player to reach 100 Bundesliga appearances when he started in his side's 2\u20130 defeat to Koln.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/kai-havertz-100-bundesliga-appearances-for-bayer-leverkusen-at-20-8688|title=Kai Havertz: 100 Bundesliga appearances for Bayer Leverkusen at 20|publisher=Bundesliga|date=15 December 2019|accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:2019-06-11 Fu\u00dfball, M\u00e4nner, L\u00e4nderspiel, Deutschland-Estland StP 2059 LR10 by Stepro.jpg|thumb|Havertz (pictured during [[Germany national football team|Germany]]'s 8\u20130 win over [[Estonia national football team|Estonia]] in June 2019) made his senior debut nine months earlier against [[Peru national football team|Peru]].]]\n\n===Youth===\nHavertz made his debut for the [[Germany national under-16 football team|Germany national under-16 team]] on 11 November 2014, starting in the friendly match against the [[Czech Republic national under-16 football team|Czech Republic]] before being substituted out in the 57th minute for [[Tom Baack]]. The match finished as a 3\u20131 win for Germany.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dfb.de/datencenter/laenderspiel-2512/2014-2015/saison/2215057 |title=U 16 L\u00e4nderspiel: Tschechische Republik \u2013 Deutschland |trans-title=Under-16 international: Czech Republic \u2013 Germany |website=DFB.de |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |date=11 November 2014 |access-date=29 August 2018 |language=German}}</ref>\n\nHavertz was included in [[2016 UEFA European Under-17 Championship squads#Germany|Germany's squad]] for the [[2016 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]] in Azerbaijan.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dfb.de/news/detail/u-17-em-unser-team-fuer-aserbaidschan-145326/full/1/ |title=U 17-EM: Unser Team f\u00fcr Aserbaidschan |trans-title=European Under-17 Championship: Our team for Azerbaijan |website=DFB.de |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |date=4 May 2016 |access-date=29 August 2018 |language=German}}</ref> He appeared in all five of Germany's matches, scoring once before Germany were eliminated by [[Spain national under-17 football team|Spain]] in the semi-finals.\n\nFollowing a 15-month absence from youth internationals, Havertz made his debut for [[Germany national under-19 football team|Germany's under-19 team]], debuting on 31 August 2017 in the 0\u20130 friendly draw against [[Switzerland national under-19 football team|Switzerland]], coming on in the 72nd minute for [[Palk\u00f3 D\u00e1rdai]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dfb.de/datencenter/laenderspiel-1355/2017-2018/saison/2258210 |title=U 19 L\u00e4nderspiel: Schweiz \u2013 Deutschland |trans-title=Under-19 international: Switzerland \u2013 Germany |website=DFB.de |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |date=31 August 2017 |access-date=29 August 2018 |language=German}}</ref> On 4 October 2017, in his third appearance for the under-19 team, Havertz scored four goals in a 5\u20131 win against [[Belarus national football team|Belarus]] in the first round of [[2018 UEFA European Under-19 Championship qualification|European Under-19 Championship qualifying]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dfb.de/datencenter/em-qualifikation-1231/2017-2018/gruppe-2/2258228 |title=U 19 EM Qualifikation: Deutschland \u2013 Wei\u00dfrussland |trans-title=Under-19 Euro qualification: Germany \u2013 Belarus |website=DFB.de |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |date=4 October 2017 |access-date=29 August 2018 |language=German}}</ref> He was later named captain of the under-19 side.<ref name=fcu>{{cite news|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/kai-havertz-leroy-sane-germany-squad-france-uefa-nations-league-511492.jsp|title=Kai Havertz receives maiden Germany call-up for UEFA Nations League opener with France|publisher=Bundesliga|date=30 August 2018|accessdate=30 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Senior===\nOn 29 August 2018, Havertz was called up to [[Germany national football team|Germany's senior team]] for the first time by head coach [[Joachim L\u00f6w]]. He was included in the squad for Germany's [[2018\u201319 UEFA Nations League|UEFA Nations League]] match against [[France national football team|France]] and friendly against [[Peru national football team|Peru]].<ref name=fcu/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dfb.de/news/detail/nations-league-drei-neue-drei-rueckkehrer-191761/ |title=Nations League: Drei Neue, drei R\u00fcckkehrer |trans-title=Nations League: Three new players, three returnees |website=DFB.de |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |date=29 August 2018 |access-date=29 August 2018 |language=German}}</ref> Havertz made his international debut on 9 September 2018, coming on as a substitute in the 88th minute for [[Timo Werner]] against Peru, with the match finishing as a 2\u20131 home win for Germany.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/nationalelf/startseite/fussball-nationalteams-freundschaftsspiele/2018/5/4212631/spielbericht_deutschland_peru.html |title=Erstes Spiel, erstes Tor: Deb\u00fctant Schulz trifft zum Sieg |trans-title=First match, first goal: debutant Schulz scores for victory |website=kicker.de |publisher=[[Kicker (sports magazine)|kicker-sportmagazin]] |date=9 September 2018 |access-date=10 September 2018 |language=German}}</ref> Upon making his debut, he became the first player born in 1999 to represent the national team.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=2590311.html|title=Scout Report: Leverkusen midfielder Kai Havertz|publisher=UEFA|date=20 February 2019|accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nHavertz has been described as technically-gifted, two-footed midfielder who is comfortable with the ball on either foot and adept with his head.<ref name=desc>{{cite news|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/kai-havertz-becoming-bayer-leverkusen-real-deal-513972.jsp|title=Kai Havertz becoming the real deal at Bayer Leverkusen|publisher=Bundesliga|date=15 October 2018|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> During his formative years, his style of play drew early comparisons to compatriot [[Mesut \u00d6zil]], with Havertz himself admitting the [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] midfielder was a player he looked up to.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.welt.de/sport/fussball/bundesliga/bayer-leverkusen/article162224749/Dieser-17-Jaehrige-gilt-als-Deutschlands-neuer-Oezil.html|title=Dieser 17-J\u00e4hrige gilt als Deutschlands neuer \u00d6zil|website=Welt|last=Wallrodt|first=Lars|date=21 February 2017|accessdate=6 April 2017}}{{in lang|de}}</ref> By the age of 19, and following numerous impressive performances in the Bundesliga, further comparisons had been drawn between Havertz and former Leverkusen players such as [[Michael Ballack]], [[Toni Kroos]] and [[Arturo Vidal]], and German media began describing him as a combination of the lot and an ''Allesk\u00f6nner'' \u2013 a player who can do everything.<ref name=desc/>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\n{{updated|12 March 2020|<ref>{{cite web|title=Kai Havertz Socceway Profile|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/kai-havertz/440864/|accessdate=21 February 2017}}</ref>}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup{{efn|Includes [[DFB-Pokal]]}}\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]]\n|[[2016\u201317 Bayer 04 Leverkusen season|2016\u201317]]\n|[[Bundesliga]]\n|24||4||1||0||3{{efn|name=UCL|Appearance(s) in [[UEFA Champions League]]}}||0||28||4\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 Bayer 04 Leverkusen season|2017\u201318]]\n|Bundesliga\n|30||3||5||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||35||4\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Bayer 04 Leverkusen season|2018\u201319]]\n|Bundesliga\n|34||17||2||0||6{{efn|name=UEL|Appearance(s) in [[UEFA Europa League]]}}||3||42||20\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 Bayer 04 Leverkusen season|2019\u201320]]\n|Bundesliga\n|22||6||4||1||8{{efn|Five appearances in [[UEFA Champions League]], three appearance and three goals in [[UEFA Europa League]]}}||3||34||10\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Totals!!110!!30!!12!!2!!17!!6!!139!!38\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career totals!!110!!30!!12!!2!!17!!6!!139!!38\n|}\n'''Notes'''\n{{Notelist}}\n\n===International===\n{{updated|13 October 2019|<ref>{{NFT player|71914}}</ref>}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|[[Germany national football team|Germany]]\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|2018||2||0\n|-\n|2019||5||1\n|-\n!Total!!7!!1\n|}\n\n====International goals====\n:''Scores and results list Germany's goal tally first.''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! # !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1 || 9 October 2019 || [[Signal Iduna Park]], [[Dortmund]], Germany || {{fb|ARG}} || align=center | '''2'''\u20130 || align=center | 2\u20132 || [[Exhibition game#Association football|Friendly]]\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===Individual===\n'''Medals'''\n* [[Fritz Walter Medal]]: U17 Silver - 2016<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dfb.de/news/detail/fritz-walter-medaille-fuer-ehegoetz-henrichs-und-itter-151343/ |title=Fritz-Walter-Medaille f\u00fcr Eheg\u00f6tz, Henrichs und Itter |trans-title=Fritz Walter Medal for Eheg\u00f6tz, Henrichs and Itter |website=DFB.de |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |date=8 August 2016 |access-date=29 August 2018 |language=German}}</ref>\n* [[Fritz Walter Medal]]: U19 Gold - 2018<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dfb.de/news/detail/fritz-walter-medaille-in-gold-an-havertz-katterbach-und-pawollek-190126/ |title=Fritz-Walter-Medaille in Gold an Havertz, Katterbach und Pawollek |trans-title=Fritz Walter medal in gold for Havertz, Katterbach and Pawollek |website=DFB.de |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |date=24 July 2018 |access-date=29 August 2018 |language=German}}</ref>\n\n'''Other'''\n* [[Bundesliga]] Team of the Year: [[2018\u201319 Bundesliga|2018\u201319]]<ref>{{cite web | url = https://tots.bundesliga.com/en/ | title = This is the Team of the season 2018/19 | publisher = bundesliga.com | date = 27 May 2019 | accessdate = 30 October 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Bundesliga]] Player of the Month: [[2018\u201319 Bundesliga|April 2019]], May 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/player-of-the-month-2018-19-ea-sports-fifa-19-2583-803|title=Bayer Leverkusen's Kai Havertz wins Bundesliga Player of the Month for May!|last=|first=|date=May 2019|website=Bundesliga|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n*[[UEFA Champions League]] Breakthrough XI: 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2635905.html|title=Champions League breakthrough team of 2019|last=|first=|date=30 December 2019|website=UEFA.com|publisher=UEFA.com Reporters & Editors|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{WorldFootball.net}}\n*{{Soccerway}}\n*{{UEFA player}}\n*{{DFB|350659<!-- kai-havertz -->}}\n*{{Kicker|<!-- havertz-kai- -->86141}}\n\n{{Bayer 04 Leverkusen squad}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards\n|bg = gold\n|fg = navy\n|list1 =\n{{Fritz Walter Medal Under-17}}\n{{Fritz Walter Medal Under-19}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Havertz, Kai}}\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Aachen]]\n[[Category:Footballers from North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n[[Category:German footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Bayer 04 Leverkusen players]]\n[[Category:Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:Germany youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Germany international footballers]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:4829:5100:8476:1602:c439:4139", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kai_Havertz"}
{"title_page": "Aimee-Ffion Edwards", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Aimee-Ffion Edwards\n| image        =\n| image_size   =\n| caption      =\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1987|11|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Newport, Wales]]\n| occupation   = Actress\n| years_active = 2002\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Aimee-Ffion Edwards''' (born 21 November 1987) is a Welsh actress.<ref name=WalesOnline>{{cite web|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/five-fun-facts-welsh-actress-7238894|title=Actress Aimee-Ffion Edwards bags new BBC Four role. But who is she? We play 'Detectorist' to find out|author=Kathryn Williams|date=9 June 2014|publisher=Wales Online|accessdate=2 November 2014}}</ref> She is known for playing [[Sketch (Skins character)|Sketch]] in ''[[Skins (UK TV series)|Skins]]'', Esme Shelby in ''[[Peaky Blinders (TV series)|Peaky Blinders]]'', Sophie in ''[[Detectorists]]'' and Abi in ''[[Loaded (TV series)|Loaded]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nAimee-Ffion Edwards was born in Newport, Wales. She attended Ysgol Gymraeg Casnewydd (Newport Welsh medium primary school) and Ysgol Gyfun Gwynllyw. She played for a local youth rugby team, the only girl in a boys' team, until she was 14. She would often go from ballet lessons to playing for the rugby team.<ref>Personal conversations 2006</ref>\n\nShe took a drama A-level at school, and joined the National Youth Theatre of Wales.<ref name=\"WalesOnline2\" />\n\nShe is fluent in English and Welsh.\n\n==Career==\n===Film and television===\nEdwards appeared in the 2002 short film ''D\u0175r Dwfn''.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=British Council|title=DWR DWfN (Food Tokens and Deep Water)|date=7 September 2006|accessdate=2 November 2014|url=http://film.britishcouncil.org/dwr-dwfn-food-tokens-and-deep-water}}</ref>\n\nShe was training to be a classical singer when she appeared on the ''[[Pop Idol]]''-type [[Welsh language]] TV show called ''[[Wawffactor]]'' in 2006, finishing as runner-up.<ref name=WalesOnline2/>\n\nEdwards made her television debut as the character Sketch in the [[E4 (TV channel)|E4]] series ''[[Skins (UK TV series)|Skins]]'' in 2008.<ref name=WalesOnline2/>\n\nIn 2009, she appeared in the Valentine's Day episode of ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]'' (\"Stand By Me\"), as a teenager who finds a replacement speed-date in the wards of Holby City Hospital, and ends up involved in a serious gun-related incident. In the first episode of ''[[Casualty 1909]]'' she played a young prostitute called Deborah Lynch, who was being abused by her father.\n\nIn 2010, she appeared in an episode of the supernatural BBC drama series ''[[Being Human (UK TV series)|Being Human]]'' as a theatre usher, who is also a ghost.\n\nIn 2011, she appeared in series 2 of the [[BBC]] drama series ''[[Luther (TV series)|Luther]]'', playing the character Jenny Jones.<ref name=WalesOnline2>{{cite web|publisher=Wales Online|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/lifestyle/showbiz/newport-actress-aimee-takes-tough-1826584|title=Newport actress Aimee takes on a tough role in Luther|date=11 June 2011|accessdate=2 November 2014|author=Rachel Mainwaring}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, she appeared in [[Sky Atlantic]]'s four-part series ''Walking And Talking'', a spin-off from an episode of [[Sky One]]'s Christmas series of shorts ''[[Little Crackers]]''. Aimee played Mary, friend of Kath, played by Ami Metcalf, in these stories written by Kathy Burke and based on her own teenage years.\n\nIn 2013 and 2014, she appeared as Esme, the wife of John Shelby, in the BBC series ''[[Peaky Blinders (TV series)|Peaky Blinders]]''.\n\nIn 2014, Edwards appeared in two [[BBC Cymru Wales]] television productions celebrating the centenary of [[Dylan Thomas]]: as part of an all-Welsh cast in a  television adaptation of Thomas' radio drama ''[[Under Milk Wood]]'', playing the part 'Laugharne Voice';<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/episode/cvzt2w/under-milk-wood |title=Under Milk Wood |publisher=[[Radio Times]] |accessdate=3 February 2016}}</ref> and as Marianne  in ''[[A Poet in New York]]'', [[Andrew Davies (writer)|Andrew Davies]]' dramatisation of Thomas' last days.<ref name=\"Poet\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p01w6llk |title=Dylan Thomas: A Poet in New York |publisher=[[BBC Two]] |year=2014 |accessdate=3 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, she appeared as Katy in \"[[The Harrowing (Inside No. 9)|The Harrowing]]\",<ref name=WalesOnline/> the sixth episode of the first series of ''[[Inside No. 9]]'', written by [[Steve Pemberton]] and [[Reece Shearsmith]].\n\nEdwards played Sophie in the [[2015 British Academy Television Awards|BAFTA]] award-winning [[BBC Four]] comedy series ''[[Detectorists]]''; series 1 in 2014 and series 2 in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bafta TV awards 2015: Winners in full |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-32215563 |date=10 May 2015 |accessdate=24 October 2017 |publisher=[[BBC]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/11135378/Detectorists-BBC-Four-review-first-rate-writing.html|title=Detectorists, BBC Four, review: 'first-rate writing'|author=Rupert Hawksley|date=2 October 2014|accessdate=2 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Detectorists Episode 3, Series 2, Episode 3 of 6 |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06nxyd8 |year= 2017 |accessdate=24 October 2017 |publisher=[[BBC]] }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, she appeared as Sian in ''[[Death in Paradise (TV series)|Death In Paradise]]'' as a young girl who is murdered.\n\nIn 2017, she was Josh's (ex)-girlfriend in the Channel 4 comedy ''[[Loaded (TV series)|Loaded]]''.\n\n===Stage===\nEdwards made her stage debut in 2008 in ''SH*T-M*X'' at the Trafalgar Studios in London.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Financial Times|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/1aa46d04-909c-11dd-8abb-0000779fd18c.html#axzz3Hq7zx0X2|date=2 October 2008|accessdate=2 November 2014|author=Ian Shuttleworth|title=SH*T-M*X, Trafalgar Studio 2, London}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, she performed in [[Jez Butterworth]]'s play ''[[Jerusalem (play)|Jerusalem]]'' at the [[Royal Court Theatre]], alongside [[Mackenzie Crook]].<ref name=WalesOnline/><ref name=WalesOnline2/>\n\nIn 2011, she made her [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] debut, reprising her role in ''Jerusalem'' at the Music Box Theatre, New York.<ref name=WalesOnline/> She appeared in the London revival of ''Jerusalem'' later that year.\n\nIn 2012, she appeared in ''[[The Recruiting Officer]]'' at the [[Donmar Warehouse]],<ref name=WalesOnline/> and in [[Marius von Mayenburg]]'s ''Fireface'' at the Young Vic.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fireface|publisher=The Stage|author=Gerald Berkowitz|date=5 October 2012|url=http://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/review.php/37520/fireface|accessdate=2 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, she appeared as Avonia Bunn in ''[[Trelawny of the Wells]]'' at the [[Donmar Warehouse]].<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/theatre-reviews/9895675/Trelawny-of-the-Wells-Donmar-Warehouse-review.html|title=Trelawny of the Wells, Donmar Warehouse, review|author=Charles Spencer|date=27 February 2013|accessdate=2 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, she played Marcella in ''B'', a new play by [[Guillermo Calder\u00f3n]] which had a limited run at the [[Royal Court Theatre]].\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Blithe Spirit (2020 film)|Blithe Spirit]]''\n| Edith\n| upcoming\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Queen and Country (film)|Queen and Country]]''\n| Sophie Adams\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|2019\n| ''[[Man Like Mobeen]]''\n| Miss Aitken\n| Series 2 Episode 4\n|-\n|2019\n| ''[[Keeping Faith (TV series)|Un Bore Mercher / Keeping Faith]]''\n| Madlen Vaughn\n| Series 2 (S4C / BBC)\n|-\n| 2018\u2013present\n| ''[[101 Dalmatian Street]]''\n| Arabella, Big Fee, Summer\n| Voice\n|-\n| 2018\u20132020\n| ''[[Thunderbirds Are Go (TV series)|Thunderbirds Are Go]]'' \n| Havoc\n| Voice \n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Troy: Fall of a City]]'' \n| [[Cassandra]]\n| TV miniseries \n|-\n|2017\n| Mister Winner (Comedy Pilot)\n| Jemma\n| BBC1 Comedy Pilot\n|-\n|2017\n| ''[[Loaded (TV series)|Loaded]]''\n| Abby\n| Channel 4 series\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Death in Paradise (TV series)|Death in Paradise]]''\n|Sian Evans \n| Series 5 Episode 8 \"Flames of Love\"\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Wolf Hall (miniseries)|Wolf Hall]]''\n| [[Elizabeth Barton]]\n|\n|- \n| 2014\u20132017\n| ''[[Detectorists]]''\n| Sophie\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Inside No. 9]]''\n| Katy\n| Episode: \"[[The Harrowing (Inside No. 9)|The Harrowing]]\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b03y7n5p |title=The Harrowing, Inside No. 9, Series 1 Episode 6 of 6 |publisher=[[BBC Two]] |year=2014 |accessdate=3 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Under Milk Wood (2014 film)|Under Milk Wood]]''\n| Laugharne Voice\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[A Poet in New York]]''\n| Marianne\n| <ref name=\"Poet\"/>\n|-\n| 2013 \u2013 \n| ''[[Peaky Blinders (TV series)|Peaky Blinders]]''\n| Esme Shelby\n|\n|- \n| 2011\n| ''[[Luther (TV series)|Luther]]''\n| Jenny Jones\n|\n|- \n| 2010\n| ''[[Being Human (UK TV series)|Being Human]]''\n| Robin\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p006fh7p |title=Being Human |publisher=[[BBC Three]] |date=12 February 2010 |accessdate=3 February 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Skins (UK TV series)|Skins]]''\n| Sketch\n|\n|}\n\n===Video games===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Everybody's Gone to the Rapture]]''\n| Rachel Baker\n| Voice role\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|2929682}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Edwards, Aimee-Ffion}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Welsh actresses]]\n[[Category:People from Newport, Wales]]\n[[Category:Welsh stage actresses]]\n[[Category:Welsh television actresses]]\n[[Category:Welsh film actresses]]\n[[Category:Welsh voice actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Aimee-Ffion Edwards\n| image        =\n| image_size   =\n| caption      =\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1987|11|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Newport, Wales]]\n| occupation   = Actress\n| years_active = 2002\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Aimee-Ffion Edwards''' (born 21 November 1987) is a Welsh actress.<ref name=WalesOnline>{{cite web|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/five-fun-facts-welsh-actress-7238894|title=Actress Aimee-Ffion Edwards bags new BBC Four role. But who is she? We play 'Detectorist' to find out|author=Kathryn Williams|date=9 June 2014|publisher=Wales Online|accessdate=2 November 2014}}</ref> She is known for playing [[Sketch (Skins character)|Sketch]] in ''[[Skins (UK TV series)|Skins]]'', Esme Shelby in ''[[Peaky Blinders (TV series)|Peaky Blinders]]'', Sophie in ''[[Detectorists]]'' and Abi in ''[[Loaded (TV series)|Loaded]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nAimee-Ffion Edwards was born in Newport, Wales. She attended Ysgol Gymraeg Casnewydd (Newport Welsh medium primary school) and Ysgol Gyfun Gwynllyw. She played for a local youth rugby team, the only girl in a boys' team, until she was 14. She would often go from ballet lessons to playing for the rugby team.<ref>Personal conversations 2006</ref>\n\nShe took a drama A-level at school, and joined the National Youth Theatre of Wales.<ref name=\"WalesOnline2\" />\n\nShe is fluent in English and Welsh.\n\n==Career==\n===Film and television===\nEdwards appeared in the 2002 short film ''D\u0175r Dwfn''.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=British Council|title=DWR DWfN (Food Tokens and Deep Water)|date=7 September 2006|accessdate=2 November 2014|url=http://film.britishcouncil.org/dwr-dwfn-food-tokens-and-deep-water}}</ref>\n\nShe was training to be a classical singer when she appeared on the ''[[Pop Idol]]''-type [[Welsh language]] TV show called ''[[Wawffactor]]'' in 2006, finishing as runner-up.<ref name=WalesOnline2/>\n\nEdwards made her television debut as the character Sketch in the [[E4 (TV channel)|E4]] series ''[[Skins (UK TV series)|Skins]]'' in 2008.<ref name=WalesOnline2/>\n\nIn 2009, she appeared in the Valentine's Day episode of ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]'' (\"Stand By Me\"), as a teenager who finds a replacement speed-date in the wards of Holby City Hospital, and ends up involved in a serious gun-related incident. In the first episode of ''[[Casualty 1909]]'' she played a young prostitute called Deborah Lynch, who was being abused by her father.\n\nIn 2010, she appeared in an episode of the supernatural BBC drama series ''[[Being Human (UK TV series)|Being Human]]'' as a theatre usher, who is also a ghost.\n\nIn 2011, she appeared in series 2 of the [[BBC]] drama series ''[[Luther (TV series)|Luther]]'', playing the character Jenny Jones.<ref name=WalesOnline2>{{cite web|publisher=Wales Online|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/lifestyle/showbiz/newport-actress-aimee-takes-tough-1826584|title=Newport actress Aimee takes on a tough role in Luther|date=11 June 2011|accessdate=2 November 2014|author=Rachel Mainwaring}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, she appeared in [[Sky Atlantic]]'s four-part series ''Walking And Talking'', a spin-off from an episode of [[Sky One]]'s Christmas series of shorts ''[[Little Crackers]]''. Aimee played Mary, friend of Kath, played by Ami Metcalf, in these stories written by Kathy Burke and based on her own teenage years.\n\nIn 2013 and 2014, she appeared as Esme, the wife of John Shelby, in the BBC series ''[[Peaky Blinders (TV series)|Peaky Blinders]]''.\n\nIn 2014, Edwards appeared in two [[BBC Cymru Wales]] television productions celebrating the centenary of [[Dylan Thomas]]: as part of an all-Welsh cast in a  television adaptation of Thomas' radio drama ''[[Under Milk Wood]]'', playing the part 'Laugharne Voice';<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/episode/cvzt2w/under-milk-wood |title=Under Milk Wood |publisher=[[Radio Times]] |accessdate=3 February 2016}}</ref> and as Marianne  in ''[[A Poet in New York]]'', [[Andrew Davies (writer)|Andrew Davies]]' dramatisation of Thomas' last days.<ref name=\"Poet\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p01w6llk |title=Dylan Thomas: A Poet in New York |publisher=[[BBC Two]] |year=2014 |accessdate=3 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, she appeared as Katy in \"[[The Harrowing (Inside No. 9)|The Harrowing]]\",<ref name=WalesOnline/> the sixth episode of the first series of ''[[Inside No. 9]]'', written by [[Steve Pemberton]] and [[Reece Shearsmith]].\n\nEdwards played Sophie in the [[2015 British Academy Television Awards|BAFTA]] award-winning [[BBC Four]] comedy series ''[[Detectorists]]''; series 1 in 2014 and series 2 in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bafta TV awards 2015: Winners in full |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-32215563 |date=10 May 2015 |accessdate=24 October 2017 |publisher=[[BBC]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/11135378/Detectorists-BBC-Four-review-first-rate-writing.html|title=Detectorists, BBC Four, review: 'first-rate writing'|author=Rupert Hawksley|date=2 October 2014|accessdate=2 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Detectorists Episode 3, Series 2, Episode 3 of 6 |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06nxyd8 |year= 2017 |accessdate=24 October 2017 |publisher=[[BBC]] }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, she appeared as Sian in ''[[Death in Paradise (TV series)|Death In Paradise]]'' as a young girl who is murdered.\n\nIn 2017, she was Josh's (ex)-girlfriend in the Channel 4 comedy ''[[Loaded (TV series)|Loaded]]''.\n\n===Stage===\nEdwards made her stage debut in 2008 in ''SH*T-M*X'' at the Trafalgar Studios in London.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Financial Times|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/1aa46d04-909c-11dd-8abb-0000779fd18c.html#axzz3Hq7zx0X2|date=2 October 2008|accessdate=2 November 2014|author=Ian Shuttleworth|title=SH*T-M*X, Trafalgar Studio 2, London}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, she performed in [[Jez Butterworth]]'s play ''[[Jerusalem (play)|Jerusalem]]'' at the [[Royal Court Theatre]], alongside [[Mackenzie Crook]].<ref name=WalesOnline/><ref name=WalesOnline2/>\n\nIn 2011, she made her [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] debut, reprising her role in ''Jerusalem'' at the Music Box Theatre, New York.<ref name=WalesOnline/> She appeared in the London revival of ''Jerusalem'' later that year.\n\nIn 2012, she appeared in ''[[The Recruiting Officer]]'' at the [[Donmar Warehouse]],<ref name=WalesOnline/> and in [[Marius von Mayenburg]]'s ''Fireface'' at the Young Vic.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fireface|publisher=The Stage|author=Gerald Berkowitz|date=5 October 2012|url=http://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/review.php/37520/fireface|accessdate=2 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, she appeared as Avonia Bunn in ''[[Trelawny of the Wells]]'' at the [[Donmar Warehouse]].<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/theatre-reviews/9895675/Trelawny-of-the-Wells-Donmar-Warehouse-review.html|title=Trelawny of the Wells, Donmar Warehouse, review|author=Charles Spencer|date=27 February 2013|accessdate=2 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, she played Marcella in ''B'', a new play by [[Guillermo Calder\u00f3n]] which had a limited run at the [[Royal Court Theatre]].\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Blithe Spirit (2020 film)|Blithe Spirit]]''\n| Edith\n| upcoming\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Queen and Country (film)|Queen and Country]]''\n| Sophie Adams\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|2019\n| ''[[Man Like Mobeen]]''\n| Miss Aitken\n| Series 2 Episode 4\n|-\n|2019\n| ''[[Keeping Faith (TV series)|Un Bore Mercher / Keeping Faith]]''\n| Madlen Vaughn\n| Series 2 (S4C / BBC)\n|-\n| 2018\u2013present\n| ''[[101 Dalmatian Street]]''\n| Arabella, Big Fee, Summer\n| Voice\n|-\n| 2018\u20132020\n| ''[[Thunderbirds Are Go (TV series)|Thunderbirds Are Go]]'' \n| Havoc\n| Voice \n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Troy: Fall of a City]]'' \n| [[Cassandra]]\n| TV miniseries \n|-\n|2017\n| Mister Winner (Comedy Pilot)\n| Jemma\n| BBC1 Comedy Pilot\n|-\n|2017\n| ''[[Loaded (TV series)|Loaded]]''\n| Abby\n| Channel 4 series\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Death in Paradise (TV series)|Death in Paradise]]''\n|Sian Evans \n| Series 5 Episode 8 \"Flames of Love\"\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Wolf Hall (miniseries)|Wolf Hall]]''\n| [[Elizabeth Barton]]\n|\n|- \n| 2014\u20132017\n| ''[[Detectorists]]''\n| Sophie\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Inside No. 9]]''\n| Katy\n| Episode: \"[[The Harrowing (Inside No. 9)|The Harrowing]]\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b03y7n5p |title=The Harrowing, Inside No. 9, Series 1 Episode 6 of 6 |publisher=[[BBC Two]] |year=2014 |accessdate=3 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Under Milk Wood (2014 film)|Under Milk Wood]]''\n| Laugharne Voice\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[A Poet in New York]]''\n| Marianne\n| <ref name=\"Poet\"/>\n|-\n| 2013 \u2013 \n| ''[[Peaky Blinders (TV series)|Peaky Blinders]]''\n| Esme Shelby\n|\n|- \n| 2011\n| ''[[Luther (TV series)|Luther]]''\n| Jenny Jones\n|\n|- \n| 2010\n| ''[[Being Human (UK TV series)|Being Human]]''\n| Robin\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p006fh7p |title=Being Human |publisher=[[BBC Three]] |date=12 February 2010 |accessdate=3 February 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Skins (UK TV series)|Skins]]''\n| Sketch\n|\n|}\n\n===Video games===\n{| class