{"title_page": "Adrian Poynton", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox writer  <!--For more information, see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]].-->\n| name = Adrian Poynton\n| honorific_prefix = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| pseudonym = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1979}}\n| birth_place = [[Burton on Trent]], [[Staffordshire]], England, United Kingdom\n| death_date = <!-- {{death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place = \n| resting_place = \n| occupation = [[Screenwriter]], [[Playwright]], [[Television producer|Producer]], Stand Up Comedian\n| language = \n| nationality = British\n| citizenship = \n| education = \n| alma_mater = \n| period = \n| genre = <!-- or: | genres =     -->\n| subject = <!-- or: | subjects =   -->\n| movement = \n| notableworks = [[White Van Man (TV series)|White Van Man]], [[Family Tools]], A Very Naughty Boy, [[Trollied]]\n| spouse = <!-- or: | spouses =    -->\n| partner = <!-- or: | partners =   -->\n| children = \n| relatives = \n| awards = \n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| years_active = \n| module = \n| website = {{URL|www.adrianpoynton.com}}\n| portaldisp = <!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc; or omit -->\n| ethnicity = \n}}\n'''Adrian Poynton''' (born 29 January 1979) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[screenwriter]], [[playwright]] and [[stand up comedian]]. He is best known as the creator and writer of [[BBC Three]] comedy ''[[White Van Man (TV series)|White Van Man]]'' and its American remake ''[[Family Tools]]''.\n\n== Biography ==\nBorn in Staffordshire in 1979, Poynton attended [[John Taylor High School]] at [[Barton-under-Needwood]] in Staffordshire in the early 1990s.  He first began performing as a member of the Lichfield Youth Theatre.\n\nFor many years he toured as a [[Stand-up comedy|stand up comedian]] regularly performing in comedy clubs and theaters across the UK and Europe.  He was also one of the UK's most popular TV studio audience warm-ups.\n\n==Writing career==\nIn 2003 his play, ''A Very Naughty Boy'' based on the life of [[Monty Python]]'s [[Graham Chapman]], won an [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]] First award.  It then had a national tour followed by a West End run at London's [[Soho Theatre]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/08/21/1061434983585.html?from=storyrhs|title=Hills tipped to hoist comedy prize|last=Low|first=Lenny Ann|date=2003-08-22|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=2009-08-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2004/apr/25/theatre3|title=Pythons' bad boy uncoiled|last=Merritt|first=Stephanie|date=2004-04-25|work=[[The Observer]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|accessdate=2009-08-13}}</ref>\n\nDuring this time he was also writing scripts for children's Television.  His scripts having appeared on [[CBBC]], [[CBeebies]] and [[Disney Channel|The Disney Channel]].\n\nIn 2011 he created and wrote the highly rated [[BBC Three]] sitcom, ''[[White Van Man (TV series)|White Van Man]]''.  It held the record for being the highest rated launch of a comedy ever on the channel.  He can  be seen acting in two episodes, playing the role of Police Officer Martin Orsom. In 2012 ''White Van Man'' returned for a second series with Adrian once again writing all the scripts.\n\nIn 2012 he also worked on series two of supermarket sitcom ''[[Trollied]]'' for [[Sky 1|Sky One]].\n\nIn 2013 White Van Man was remade in America as ''[[Family Tools]]'' for [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] with Poynton overseeing the show, writing episodes and serving as Co-Creator and Producer. Thirteen episodes were ordered on 11 May 2012, for the first season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/05/11/abc-picks-up-comedies-the-neighbors-and-comeback-jack-and-dramas-nashville-red-window-and-zero-hour/133721 | title=ABC Picks Up Comedies 'The Neighbors' and 'The Family Tools' and Dramas 'Nashville,' 'Red Widow' and 'Zero Hour' + More | publisher=ZAP2it | work=TV by the Numbers | date=11 May 2012 | accessdate=11 May 2012 | last=Seidman | first=Robert}}</ref> It was later reported on 10 November 2012, that ABC cut their order from 13 episodes to 10 because of scheduling conflicts.<ref name=\"10eps\">{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/11/order-of-abcs-midseason-comedy-family-tools-cut-to-10-episodes | title=Order For ABC's Midseason Comedy 'Family Tools' Cut To 10 Episodes | publisher=Deadline Hollywood | date=10 November 2012 | accessdate=10 November 2012 | last=Andreeva | first=Nellie}}</ref> ''Family Tools'' was canceled on 10 May 2013, after only two episodes had aired.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/05/10/happy-endings-canceled-by-abc/182139 | title='Happy Endings', 'Family Tools', 'How to Live With Your Parents' & 'Malibu Country' Canceled by ABC | publisher=ZAP2it | work=TV by the Numbers | date=10 May 2013 | accessdate=11 May 2013 | last=Kondolojy | first=Amanda}}</ref> However, the remaining episodes aired over the summer.\n\nHe contributed audio plays for the [[Big Finish Productions|Big Finish]] [[Doctor Who]] ranges, starting with the [[Fourth Doctor]] release, ''Dethras''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bigfinish.com/releases/v/doctor-who-dethras-1236 | title=6.4. Doctor Who: Dethras  | publisher=Big Finish | accessdate=9 December 2019 }}</ref> He also wrote for the spin-off ''Jenny - The Doctor's Daughter'' starring his friend and ''White Van Man'' actress [[Georgia Tennant]].\n\nHe splits his time between London and Los Angeles through his work as a screenwriter for television and movies.\n\n== Works ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n\n=== Television ===\n* ''[[Family Tools]] (''2013)\n* ''[[White Van Man (TV series)|White Van Man]]'' (2011-2012)\n* ''[[Trollied]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Nuzzle and Scratch]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Kerwhizz]]'' (2008)\n* ''Good Morning Raoul'' (2003)\n* ''Raoul's Summer Camp'' (2004)\n\n=== Theatre ===\n* ''Happy, Woody and Me'' (2007)\n* ''Success'' (2004)\n* ''A Very Naughty Boy'' (2003)\n{{col-break}}\n\n=== Stand Up Comedy ===\n* ''Adrian Poynton: Live'' (2012)\n* ''Life, Death & Birthdays'' (2011)\n* ''Pale Blue'' (2010)\n* ''Stories About People I Used To Know'' (2009)\n* ''The New Rock n' Roll'' (2006)\n\n=== Audio Drama ===\n* ''Jenny - The Doctor's Daughter: Zero Space'' (2018)\n* ''Doctor Who: Dethras'' (2017)\n\n=== Film ===\n* ''One By One -'' as script editor (2014)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.adrianpoynton.com Official website]\n*{{IMDb name|1845845}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Poynton, Adrian}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:English comedy writers]]\n[[Category:British comedy writers]]\n[[Category:British comedians]]\n[[Category:British male writers]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:English screenwriters]]\n[[Category:English male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:British male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:English television writers]]\n[[Category:English dramatists and playwrights]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox writer  <!--For more information, see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]].-->\n| name = Adrian Poynton\n| honorific_prefix = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| pseudonym = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1979}}\n| birth_place = [[Burton on Trent]], [[Staffordshire]], England, United Kingdom\n| death_date = <!-- {{death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place = \n| resting_place = \n| occupation = [[Screenwriter]], [[Playwright]], [[Television producer|Producer]], Stand Up Comedian\n| language = \n| nationality = British\n| citizenship = \n| education = \n| alma_mater = \n| period = \n| genre = <!-- or: | genres =     -->\n| subject = <!-- or: | subjects =   -->\n| movement = \n| notableworks = [[White Van Man (TV series)|White Van Man]], [[Family Tools]], A Very Naughty Boy, [[Trollied]]\n| spouse = <!-- or: | spouses =    -->\n| partner = <!-- or: | partners =   -->\n| children = \n| relatives = \n| awards = \n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| years_active = \n| module = \n| website = {{URL|www.adrianpoynton.com}}\n| portaldisp = <!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc; or omit -->\n| ethnicity = \n}}\n'''Adrian Poynton''' (born 29 January 1979) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[screenwriter]], [[playwright]] and [[stand up comedian]]. He is best known as the creator and writer of [[BBC Three]] comedy ''[[White Van Man (TV series)|White Van Man]]'' and its American remake ''[[Family Tools]]''.\n\n== Biography ==\nBorn in Staffordshire in 1979, Poynton attended [[John Taylor High School]] at [[Barton-under-Needwood]] in Staffordshire in the early 1990s.  He first began performing as a member of the Lichfield Youth Theatre.\n\nFor many years he toured as a [[Stand-up comedy|stand up comedian]] regularly performing in comedy clubs and theaters across the UK and Europe.  He was also one of the UK's most popular TV studio audience warm-ups.\n==Writing Career==\nIn 2003 his play, ''A Very Naughty Boy'' based on the life of [[Monty Python]]'s [[Graham Chapman]], won an [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]] First award.  It then had a national tour followed by a West End run at London's [[Soho Theatre]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/08/21/1061434983585.html?from=storyrhs|title=Hills tipped to hoist comedy prize|last=Low|first=Lenny Ann|date=2003-08-22|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=2009-08-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2004/apr/25/theatre3|title=Pythons' bad boy uncoiled|last=Merritt|first=Stephanie|date=2004-04-25|work=[[The Observer]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|accessdate=2009-08-13}}</ref>\n\nDuring this time he was also writing scripts for children's Television.  His scripts having appeared on [[CBBC]], [[CBeebies]] and [[Disney Channel|The Disney Channel]].\n\nIn 2011 he created and wrote the highly rated [[BBC Three]] sitcom, ''[[White Van Man (TV series)|White Van Man]]''.  It held the record for being the highest rated launch of a comedy ever on the channel.  He can  be seen acting in two episodes, playing the role of Police Officer Martin Orsom. In 2012 ''White Van Man'' returned for a second series with Adrian once again writing all the scripts.\n\nIn 2012 he also worked on series two of supermarket sitcom ''[[Trollied]]'' for [[Sky 1|Sky One]].\n\nIn 2013 White Van Man was remade in America as ''[[Family Tools]]'' for [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] with Poynton overseeing the show, writing episodes and serving as Co-Creator and Producer. Thirteen episodes were ordered on 11 May 2012, for the first season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/05/11/abc-picks-up-comedies-the-neighbors-and-comeback-jack-and-dramas-nashville-red-window-and-zero-hour/133721 | title=ABC Picks Up Comedies 'The Neighbors' and 'The Family Tools' and Dramas 'Nashville,' 'Red Widow' and 'Zero Hour' + More | publisher=ZAP2it | work=TV by the Numbers | date=11 May 2012 | accessdate=11 May 2012 | last=Seidman | first=Robert}}</ref> It was later reported on 10 November 2012, that ABC cut their order from 13 episodes to 10 because of scheduling conflicts.<ref name=\"10eps\">{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/11/order-of-abcs-midseason-comedy-family-tools-cut-to-10-episodes | title=Order For ABC's Midseason Comedy 'Family Tools' Cut To 10 Episodes | publisher=Deadline Hollywood | date=10 November 2012 | accessdate=10 November 2012 | last=Andreeva | first=Nellie}}</ref> ''Family Tools'' was canceled on 10 May 2013, after only two episodes had aired.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/05/10/happy-endings-canceled-by-abc/182139 | title='Happy Endings', 'Family Tools', 'How to Live With Your Parents' & 'Malibu Country' Canceled by ABC | publisher=ZAP2it | work=TV by the Numbers | date=10 May 2013 | accessdate=11 May 2013 | last=Kondolojy | first=Amanda}}</ref> However, the remaining episodes aired over the summer.\n\nHe contributed audio plays for the [[Big Finish Productions|Big Finish]] [[Doctor Who]] ranges, starting with the [[Fourth Doctor]] release, ''Dethras''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bigfinish.com/releases/v/doctor-who-dethras-1236 | title=6.4. Doctor Who: Dethras  | publisher=Big Finish | accessdate=9 December 2019 }}</ref> He also wrote for the spin-off ''Jenny - The Doctor's Daughter'' starring his friend and ''White Van Man'' actress [[Georgia Tennant]].\n\nHe splits his time between London and Los Angeles through his work as a screenwriter for television and movies.\n\n== Works ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n=== Television ===\n* ''[[Family Tools]] (''2013)\n* ''[[White Van Man (TV series)|White Van Man]]'' (2011-2012)\n* ''[[Trollied]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Nuzzle and Scratch]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Kerwhizz]]'' (2008)\n* ''Good Morning Raoul'' (2003)\n* ''Raoul's Summer Camp'' (2004)\n\n=== Theatre ===\n* ''Happy, Woody and Me'' (2007)\n* ''Success'' (2004)\n* ''A Very Naughty Boy'' (2003)\n{{col-break}}\n=== Stand Up Comedy ===\n* ''Adrian Poynton: Live'' (2012)\n* ''Life, Death & Birthdays'' (2011)\n* ''Pale Blue'' (2010)\n* ''Stories About People I Used To Know'' (2009)\n* ''The New Rock n' Roll'' (2006)\n\n=== Audio Drama ===\n* ''Jenny - The Doctor's Daughter: Zero Space'' (2018)\n* ''Doctor Who: Dethras'' (2017)\n\n=== Film ===\n* ''One By One -'' as script editor (2014)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.adrianpoynton.com Official website]\n*{{IMDb name|1845845}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Poynton, Adrian}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1979 birth